# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bbc-news-british-tv-channel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] In TV streaming, high-definition television (HDTV) and video display technology, **1080i** is a video display format with 1080 lines of vertical resolution and interlaced scanning method.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This format was once a standard in HDTV.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] It was particularly used for broadcast television because it can deliver high-resolution images without needing excessive bandwidth.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This format is used in the SMPTE 292M standard.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The number "1080" in 1080i refers to the number of horizontal lines that make up the vertical resolution of the display.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] Each of these lines contributes to the overall detail and clarity of the image.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This is a technique where the image is not displayed all at once.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] Instead, the frame is split into two fields.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] One field contains the odd-numbered lines, and the other field contains the even-numbered lines.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] These fields are displayed in rapid succession, giving the appearance of a full image to the human eye.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The interlacing technique was developed to improve the motion portrayal of images without doubling the required bandwidth.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This is particularly useful in broadcasting, where bandwidth efficiency is crucial.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The frame rate is typically 50 or 60 fields per second, depending on the region.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This effectively means 25 or 30 frames per second when the fields are combined.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] A key difference between 1080i and 1080p is how the lines of resolution are displayed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] Both offer 1920x1080 pixels, but the display method is different.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] In 1080p, the "p" stands for progressive scan.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] Each frame is drawn line by line, from top to bottom, creating a complete image in a single pass.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This results in a sharper and more stable picture, especially in fast-moving scenes.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] On the other hand, 1080i uses an interlaced method.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The two fields that make up a frame are captured at slightly different times, leading to a misalignment in fast-moving parts of the image.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This can cause artifacts like "combing," where fast-moving objects appear to have a serrated edge.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] However, 1080i has been preferred in broadcast television due to its lower bandwidth requirements, making it more efficient for over-the-air or cable transmission.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The origins of 1080i can be traced from Multiple sub-Nyquist sampling encoding, a Japanese analog high-definition television system.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] 1080i emerged as a leading standard for HDTV broadcasts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The ATSC (Advanced Television Systems Committee) standards and the DVB (Digital Video Broadcasting) standards allowed for the transmission of 1080i video signals.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The adoption of 1080i was particularly significant in sports broadcasting.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The higher resolution allowed for more detail and clarity, especially in large stadium shots and fast-paced action.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The format's efficiency in utilizing available bandwidth made it a practical choice for broadcasters.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] However, it required more complex processing on the receiving end to deinterlace the image for display on progressive-scan screens.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] Overall, 1080i played a crucial role in the early days of HDTV.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] It bridged the gap between standard-definition broadcasts and the high-definition future that would soon become the norm.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] While its use has diminished with the rise of 1080p and 4K resolutions, 1080i remains an important milestone in the evolution of television technology.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This means that each video frame has 1,920 pixels horizontally and 1,080 pixels vertically.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This results in over two million individual pixels per frame.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This high resolution is why 1080i is called "high-definition".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] It offers a significant improvement over standard-definition formats, which typically have much lower pixel counts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The 1920x1080 resolution allows for greater detail and clarity in images.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This makes it ideal for larger screens where higher pixel density is essential to maintain image quality.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The increased resolution is particularly noticeable in fine details such as textures, text, and intricate patterns.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] These can be rendered with much greater accuracy than in lower-resolution formats.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This refers to how each video frame is displayed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] Instead of showing the entire frame at once, the interlacing technique divides each frame into two separate fields.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The first field contains all the odd-numbered lines (1, 3, 5, etc.), and the second field contains all the even-numbered lines (2, 4, 6, etc.).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] These two fields are displayed one after the other.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The odd lines are shown first, followed by the even lines.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This happens very quickly, around 50 or 60 fields per second.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The human eye sees these two fields as a single, continuous image.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The main advantage of interlacing is that it allows for a higher frame rate without needing more bandwidth.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This results in smoother motion, especially for content with moderate to fast movement, like sports broadcasts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] However, interlacing also has some drawbacks.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] Since the two fields are captured at slightly different times, fast-moving objects can appear misaligned between the two fields.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This creates a visual artifact called "combing." This can reduce image quality, especially in scenes with a lot of motion.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] Modern display devices often use deinterlacing algorithms to combine the two fields into a single progressive image before displaying it.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The frame rate of 1080i is usually 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] In areas using the PAL or SECAM standards, like Europe and parts of Asia, the frame rate is 50 Hz.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] In regions using NTSC, like North America and Japan, the frame rate is 60 Hz.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The frame rate refers to how often a new field is shown per second.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] At 50 Hz, 50 fields are shown each second.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This results in 25 full frames per second when the odd and even fields are combined.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] At 60 Hz, 59.94 fields are shown per second.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This results in 29.97 full frames per second.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] Interlacing affects how motion is perceived in 1080i.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] Since each field represents a slightly different moment in time, motion can appear smoother compared to lower frame rate progressive scans.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] However, this also means 1080i can struggle with fast-moving scenes.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The interlaced fields might not perfectly align, leading to motion artifacts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The European Broadcasting Union (EBU) prefers to use the resolution and *frame rate* (not field rate) separated by a slash, as in *1080i/29.97* and *1080i/25*, likewise 480i/29.97 and 576i/25.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] The 1080i video signals can be carried by four main digital television broadcast systems: ATSC, DVB, ISDB and DTMB.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] In both ATSC and DVB systems, the 1080i signal is compressed using codecs like MPEG-2 or H.264 to reduce the bandwidth required for transmission.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] In the United States, 1080i is the preferred format for most broadcasters, with Warner Bros.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] Discovery, Paramount Global, and Comcast owned networks broadcasting in the format, along with most smaller broadcasters.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] Only Fox- and Disney-owned television networks, along with MLB Network and a few other cable networks, use 720p as the preferred format for their networks; A&E Networks channels converted from 720p to 1080i sometime in 2013 due to acquired networks already transmitting in the 1080i format.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] This also allows local newscasts on these ABC affiliates to be produced in the higher resolution (especially for weather forecasting presentation purposes for map clarity) to match the picture quality of their 1080i competitors.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] Motion pictures shot on film to fit a 16:9 widescreen format (1.78:1) are typically intended to be played back at 24 frames per second.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] When telecined and played back at the PAL standard 25 frames per second, films run 4.16% faster than the original, and 4.27083% faster than the NTSC film standard 23.976023976 frames per second.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] High-definition television (HDTV) broadcast standards utilize 1080i (interlaced) or 720p (progressive) formats, typically offering 1920x1080 resolution.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] Key, region-specific formats include 1080i25 for PAL (50 fields/second), 1080i30 for NTSC (60 fields/second), and 1080i24 for film, often converted via telecine for 25/30 frames per second, 1080i50/60 broadcasts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/1080i] PAL speed-up does not occur on footage intended for playback at 25 frames per second.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 26 December 2004, at 07:58:53 local time (UTC+7), a Mw 9.2–9.3 earthquake struck with its epicenter off the west coast of Aceh, in northern Sumatra, Indonesia.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The undersea megathrust earthquake, known in the scientific community as the **Sumatra–Andaman earthquake**, was caused by a rupture along the fault boundary between the Burma plate and the Indian plate, and reached a maximum Mercalli intensity of IX in some areas.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The direct result was severe disruption to living conditions and commerce in coastal provinces of these and other surrounding countries.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It is the deadliest tsunami in history, the deadliest natural disaster of the 21st century, and one of the deadliest natural disasters in recorded history.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It is also the worst natural disaster in the history of Indonesia, the Maldives, Sri Lanka, and Thailand.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake itself is the most powerful earthquake ever recorded in Asia, the strongest of the 21st century, and the second- or third-most powerful globally since modern seismography began in 1900.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It had the longest fault rupture ever observed, between 1,200 to 1,300 kilometres (746 to 808 mi), and had the longest duration of faulting ever observed, lasting at least ten minutes.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It caused the entire planet to vibrate by as much as 10 mm (0.4 in), and also remotely triggered earthquakes as far away as Alaska.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Its epicentre was located between Simeulue and mainland Sumatra.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The plight of the affected people and countries prompted a worldwide humanitarian response, with donations totaling more than US$14 billion (equivalent to US$24 billion in 2025 currency).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake was initially documented as having a moment magnitude of 8.8.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The United States Geological Survey has its official estimate of Mw9.1, but most recent studies suggest that the earthquake was Mw9.2–9.3.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Hiroo Kanamori of the California Institute of Technology estimates that Mw9.2 is the most representative estimate of the earthquake's size.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] More recent studies estimate the magnitude to be Mw9.3.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 2016 study estimated the magnitude to be Mw9.25, while a 2021 study revised its 2007 estimate of Mw9.1 to a new magnitude of Mw9.2.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The hypocentre of the main earthquake was approximately 160 km (100 mi) off the western coast of northern Sumatra, in the Indian Ocean just north of Simeulue island at a depth of 30 km (19 mi) below sea level (initially reported as 10 km or 6.2 mi).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The northern section of the Sunda megathrust ruptured over a length of 1,300 km (810 mi).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake (followed by the tsunami) was felt in Bangladesh, India, Malaysia, Myanmar, Thailand, Sri Lanka and the Maldives.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Splay faults, or secondary "pop up faults", caused long, narrow parts of the seafloor to pop up in seconds.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This rapidly increased the height and speed of the tsunami waves, destroying the nearby Indonesian town of Lhoknga.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Indonesia lies between the Pacific Ring of Fire along the northeastern islands adjacent to New Guinea, and the Alpide belt that runs along the south and west from Sumatra, Java, Bali, Flores to Timor.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The 2002 Sumatra earthquake is believed to have been a foreshock, preceding the main event by over two years.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Great earthquakes such as the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake are generally associated with megathrust events in subduction zones.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Their seismic moments can account for a significant fraction of the global seismic moment across century-scale periods.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Of all the moment released by earthquakes in the 100 years from 1906 through 2005, roughly one-eighth was due to the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This quake, together with the Great Alaskan earthquake (1964) and the Great Chilean earthquake (1960), account for almost half of the total moment.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Since 1900, the only earthquakes recorded with a greater magnitude were the 1960 Chile earthquake (magnitude 9.5) and the 1964 Alaska earthquake in Prince William Sound (magnitude 9.2).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The only other recorded earthquakes of magnitude 9.0 or greater were off Kamchatka, Russia, in November 1952 (magnitude 9.0) and Tōhoku, Japan, in March 2011 (magnitude 9.1).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Each of these megathrust earthquakes also spawned tsunamis in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In comparison to the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake, the death toll from these earthquakes and tsunamis was significantly lower, primarily because of the lower population density along the coasts near affected areas.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Comparisons with earlier earthquakes are difficult, as earthquake strength was not measured systematically until the 1930s.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, historical earthquake strength can sometimes be estimated by examining historical descriptions of the damage caused, and the geological records of the areas where they occurred.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Some examples of significant historical megathrust earthquakes are the 1868 Arica earthquake in Peru and the 1700 Cascadia earthquake in western North America.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake was unusually large in geographical and geological extent.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] An estimated 1,600 km (1,000 mi) of fault surface slipped (or ruptured) about 15 m (50 ft) along the subduction zone where the Indian plate slides under (or subducts) the overriding Burma plate.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The rupture proceeded at about 2.8 km/s (1.74 mi/s; 10,100 km/h; 6,260 mph), beginning off the coast of Aceh and proceeding north-westerly over about 100 seconds.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] After a pause of about another 100 seconds, the rupture continued northwards towards the Andaman and Nicobar Islands.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The northern rupture occurred more slowly than in the south, at about 2.1 km/s (1.3 mi/s; 7,600 km/h; 4,700 mph), continuing north for another five minutes to a plate boundary where the fault type changes from subduction to strike-slip (the two plates slide past one another in opposite directions).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Indian plate is part of the Indo-Australian plate, which underlies the Indian Ocean and Bay of Bengal, and is moving north-east at an average of 60 mm/a (2.4 in/year).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The India Plate meets the Burma plate (which is considered a portion of the great Eurasian plate) at the Sunda Trench.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At this point, the India Plate subducts beneath the Burma plate, which carries the Nicobar Islands, the Andaman Islands, and northern Sumatra.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The India Plate sinks deeper and deeper beneath the Burma plate until the increasing temperature and pressure drive volatiles out of the subducting plate.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] These volatiles rise into the overlying plate, causing partial melting and the formation of magma.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The rising magma intrudes into the crust above and exits the Earth's crust through volcanoes in the form of a volcanic arc.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The volcanic activity that results as the Indo-Australian plate subducts the Eurasian plate has created the Sunda Arc.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As well as the sideways movement between the plates, the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake resulted in a rise of the seafloor by several metres, displacing an estimated 30 km3 (7.2 cu mi) of water and triggering devastating tsunami waves.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The waves radiated outwards along the entire 1,600 km (1,000 mi) length of the rupture (acting as a line source).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This greatly increased the geographical area over which the waves were observed, reaching as far as Mexico, Chile, and the Arctic.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The raising of the seafloor significantly reduced the capacity of the Indian Ocean, producing a permanent rise in the global sea level by an estimated 0.1 mm (0.004 in).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Numerous aftershocks were reported off the Andaman Islands, the Nicobar Islands and the region of the original epicentre in the hours and days that followed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The magnitude 8.6 2005 Nias–Simeulue earthquake, which originated off the coast of the Sumatran island of Nias, is not considered an aftershock, despite its proximity to the epicentre, and was most likely triggered by stress changes associated with the 2004 event.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake produced its own aftershocks, some registering a magnitude of as high as 6.9.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Other aftershocks of up to magnitude 7.2 continued to shake the region daily for three or four months.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As well as continuing aftershocks, the energy released by the original earthquake continued to make its presence felt well after the event.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A week after the earthquake, its reverberations could still be measured, providing valuable scientific data about the Earth's interior.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake came just three days after a magnitude 8.1 earthquake in the sub-antarctic Auckland Islands, an uninhabited region southwest of New Zealand, and Macquarie Island to Australia's south.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This is unusual since earthquakes of magnitude eight or more occur only about once per year on average.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Geological Survey sees no evidence of a causal relationship between these events.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake is thought to have triggered activity in both Leuser Mountain and Mount Talang, volcanoes in Aceh along the same range of peaks, while the 2005 Nias–Simeulue earthquake sparked activity in Lake Toba, a massive caldera in Sumatra.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The energy released on the Earth's surface (*M*e, the energy magnitude, which is the *seismic potential for damage*) by the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake was estimated at 1.1×1017 joules.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake generated a seismic oscillation of the Earth's surface of up to 200–300 mm (8–12 in), equivalent to the effect of the tidal forces caused by the Sun and Moon.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The seismic waves of the earthquake were felt across the planet, as far away as the U.S. state of Oklahoma, where vertical movements of 3 mm (0.12 in) were recorded.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] By February 2005, the earthquake's effects were still detectable as a 20 μm (0.02 mm; 0.0008 in) complex harmonic oscillation of the Earth's surface, which gradually diminished and merged with the incessant free oscillation of the Earth more than four months after the earthquake.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Because of its enormous energy release and shallow rupture depth, the earthquake generated remarkable seismic ground motions around the globe, particularly due to huge Rayleigh (surface) elastic waves that exceeded 10 mm (0.4 in) in vertical amplitude everywhere on Earth.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The seismograms are arranged vertically by distance from the epicentre in degrees.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earliest, lower amplitude signal is that of the compressional (P) wave, which takes about 22 minutes to reach the other side of the planet (the antipode; in this case near Ecuador).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The largest amplitude signals are seismic surface waves that reach the antipode after about 100 minutes.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The surface waves can be clearly seen to reinforce near the antipode (with the closest seismic stations in Ecuador), and to subsequently encircle the planet to return to the epicentral region after about 200 minutes.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A major aftershock (magnitude 7.1) can be seen at the closest stations starting just after the 200-minute mark.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The aftershock would be considered a major earthquake under ordinary circumstances but is dwarfed by the mainshock.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The shift of mass and the massive release of energy slightly altered the Earth's rotation.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Weeks after the earthquake, theoretical models suggested the earthquake shortened the length of a day by 2.68 microseconds, due to a decrease in the oblateness of the Earth.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It also caused the Earth to minutely "wobble" on its axis by up to 25 mm (1 in) in the direction of 145° east longitude, or perhaps by up to 50 or 60 mm (2.0 or 2.4 in).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Because of tidal effects of the Moon, the length of a day increases at an average of 15 microseconds per year, so any rotational change due to the earthquake will be lost quickly.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Similarly, the natural Chandler wobble of the Earth, which in some cases can be up to 15 m (50 ft), eventually offset the minor wobble produced by the earthquake.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] There was 10 m (33 ft) movement laterally and 4–5 m (13–16 ft) vertically along the fault line.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Since movement was vertical as well as lateral, some coastal areas may have been moved to below sea level.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Andaman and Nicobar Islands appear to have shifted south-west by around 1.25 m (4 ft 1 in) and to have sunk by 1 m (3 ft 3 in).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In February 2005, the Royal Navy vessel HMS *Scott* surveyed the seabed around the earthquake zone, which varies in depth between 1,000 and 5,000 m (550 and 2,730 fathoms; 3,300 and 16,400 ft).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The survey, conducted using a high-resolution, multi-beam sonar system, revealed that the earthquake had made a considerable impact on the topography of the seabed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] 1,500-metre-high (5,000 ft) thrust ridges created by previous geologic activity along the fault had collapsed, generating landslides several kilometres wide.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One such landslide consisted of a single block of rock some 100 m (330 ft) high and 2 km (1.2 mi) long.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The momentum of the water displaced by tectonic uplift had also dragged massive slabs of rock, each weighing millions of tonnes, as far as 10 km (6 mi) across the seabed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] An oceanic trench several kilometres wide was exposed in the earthquake zone.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The TOPEX/Poseidon and Jason-1 satellites happened to pass over the tsunami as it was crossing the ocean.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] These satellites carry radars that measure precisely the height of the water surface; anomalies in the order of 500 mm (20 in) were measured.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Measurements from these satellites may prove invaluable for the understanding of the earthquake and tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Unlike data from tide gauges installed on shores, measurements obtained in the middle of the ocean can be used for computing the parameters of the source earthquake without having to compensate for the complex ways in which proximity to the coast changes the size and shape of a wave.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Before the 2004 quake there were three arguments against a large earthquake occurring in the Sumatra region.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Previously it was thought that the convergence rate had to be fast.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Before the 2004 quake it was thought that giant earthquakes only occurred in regions without back-arc basins.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The sudden vertical rise of the seabed by several metres during the earthquake displaced massive volumes of water, resulting in a tsunami that struck the coasts of the Indian Ocean.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A tsunami that causes damage far away from its source is sometimes called a teletsunami and is much more likely to be produced by the vertical motion of the seabed than by horizontal motion.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami, like all the others, behaved differently in deep water than in shallow water.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Scientists investigating the damage in Aceh found evidence that the wave reached a height of 24 m (80 ft) when coming ashore along large stretches of the coastline, rising to 30 m (100 ft) in some areas when travelling inland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Radar satellites recorded the heights of tsunami waves in deep water: the maximum height was at 600 mm (2 ft) two hours after the earthquake, the first such observations ever made.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In many places, the waves reached as far as 2 km (1.2 mi) inland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Because the 1,600 km (1,000 mi) fault affected by the earthquake was in a nearly north–south orientation, the greatest strength of the tsunami waves was in an east–west direction.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Bangladesh, which lies at the northern end of the Bay of Bengal, had few casualties despite being a low-lying country relatively near the epicentre.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] It also benefited from the fact that the earthquake proceeded more slowly in the northern rupture zone, greatly reducing the energy of the water displacements in that region.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Coasts that have a landmass between them and the tsunami's location of origin are usually safe; however, tsunami waves can sometimes diffract around such landmasses.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Thus, the Indian state of Kerala was hit by the tsunami despite being on the country's western coast, and the western coast of Sri Lanka suffered substantial impacts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Distance alone was no guarantee of safety, as Somalia was hit harder than Bangladesh despite being much farther away.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Because of the distances involved, the tsunami took anywhere from fifteen minutes to seven hours to reach the coastlines.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The northern regions of the Indonesian island of Sumatra were hit quickly, while Sri Lanka and the east coast of India were hit roughly 90 minutes to two hours later.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Thailand was struck about two hours later despite being closer to the epicentre because the tsunami travelled more slowly in the shallow Andaman Sea off its western coast.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami was noticed as far as Struisbaai in South Africa, about 8,500 km (5,300 mi) away, where a 1.5-metre-high (5 ft) tide surged on shore about 16 hours after the earthquake.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] It took a relatively long time to reach Struisbaai at the southernmost point of Africa, probably because of the broad continental shelf off South Africa and because the tsunami would have followed the South African coast from east to west.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami also reached Antarctica, where tidal gauges at Japan's Showa Base recorded oscillations of up to a metre (3 ft 3 in), with disturbances lasting a couple of days.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Some of the tsunami's energy escaped into the Pacific Ocean, where it produced small but measurable tsunamis along the western coasts of North and South America, typically around 200 to 400 mm (7.9 to 15.7 in).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] At Manzanillo, Mexico, a tsunami with a wave height of 89.3 centimetres (2.93 ft; 35.2 in) was measured.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As well, the tsunami was large enough to be detected in Vancouver, Canada, which puzzled many scientists, as the tsunamis measured in some parts of South America were larger than those measured in some parts of the Indian Ocean.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] It has been theorized that the tsunamis were focused and directed at long ranges by the mid-ocean ridges which run along the margins of the continental plates.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Despite a delay of up to several hours between the earthquake and the impact of the tsunami, nearly all of the victims were taken by surprise.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There were no tsunami warning systems in the Indian Ocean to detect tsunamis or to warn the general population living around the ocean.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tsunami detection is difficult because while a tsunami is in deep water, it has little height and a network of sensors is needed to detect it.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tsunamis are more frequent in the Pacific Ocean than in other oceans because of earthquakes in the "Ring of Fire".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Although the extreme western edge of the Ring of Fire extends into the Indian Ocean (the point where the earthquake struck), no warning system existed in that ocean.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tsunamis there are relatively rare despite earthquakes being relatively frequent in Indonesia.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The last major tsunami was caused by the 1883 eruption of Krakatoa.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Not every earthquake produces large tsunamis: on 28 March 2005, a magnitude 8.7 earthquake hit roughly the same area of the Indian Ocean but did not result in a major tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The first warning sign of a possible tsunami is the earthquake itself.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] However, tsunamis can strike thousands of kilometres away where the earthquake is felt only weakly or not at all.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In the minutes preceding a tsunami strike, the sea sometimes recedes temporarily from the coast, which was observed on the eastern earthquake rupture zone such as the coastlines of Aceh, Phuket island and Khao Lak in Thailand, Penang island in Malaysia, and the Andaman and Nicobar islands.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] This rare sight reportedly induced people, especially children, to visit the coast to investigate and collect stranded fish on as much as 2.5 km (1.6 mi) of exposed beach, with fatal results.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] However, not all tsunamis cause this "disappearing sea" effect.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In some cases, there are no warning signs at all: the sea will suddenly swell without retreating, surprising many people and giving them little time to flee.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] One of the few coastal areas to evacuate ahead of the tsunami was on the Indonesian island of Simeulue, close to the epicentre.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Island folklore recounted an earthquake and tsunami in 1907, and the islanders fled to inland hills after the initial shaking and before the tsunami struck.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] These tales and oral folklore from previous generations may have helped the survival of the inhabitants.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On Maikhao Beach in north Phuket City, Thailand, a 10-year-old British tourist named Tilly Smith had studied tsunamis in geography at school and recognised the warning signs of the receding ocean and frothing bubbles.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] She and her parents warned others on the beach, which was evacuated safely.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] John Chroston, a biology teacher from Scotland, also recognised the signs at Kamala Bay north of Phuket, taking a busload of vacationers and locals to safety on higher ground.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Anthropologists had initially expected the aboriginal population of the Andaman Islands to be badly affected by the tsunami and even feared the already depopulated Onge tribe could have been wiped out.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Many of the aboriginal tribes evacuated and suffered fewer casualties, however.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Oral traditions developed from previous earthquakes helped the aboriginal tribes escape the tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] For example, the folklore of the Onges talks of "huge shaking of ground followed by high wall of water".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Almost all of the Onge people seemed to have survived the tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami devastated the coastline of Aceh province, about 20 minutes after the earthquake.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Banda Aceh, the closest major city, suffered severe casualties.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The sea receded and exposed the seabed, prompting locals to collect stranded fish and explore the area.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Local eyewitnesses described three large waves, with the first wave rising gently to the foundation of the buildings, followed minutes later by a sudden withdrawal of the sea near the port of Ulèë Lheuë.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] This was succeeded by the appearance of two large black-coloured steep waves which then travelled inland into the capital city as a large turbulent bore.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Eyewitnesses described the tsunami as a "black giant", "mountain" and a "wall of water".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Video footage revealed torrents of black water, surging by windows of a two-story residential area situated about 3.2 km (2.0 mi) inland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Additionally, amateur footage recorded in the middle of the city captured an approaching black surge flowing down the city streets, full of debris, inundating them.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The level of destruction was extreme on the northwestern areas of the city, immediately inland of the aquaculture ponds, and directly facing the Indian Ocean.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami height was reduced from 12 m (39 ft) at Ulèë Lheuë to 6 m (20 ft) a further 8 km (5.0 mi) to the north-east.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The inundation was observed to extend 3–4 km (1.9–2.5 mi) inland throughout the city.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Within 2–3 km (1.2–1.9 mi) of the shoreline, houses, except for strongly-built reinforced concrete ones with brick walls, which seemed to have been partially damaged by the earthquake before the tsunami attack, were swept away or destroyed by the tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The area toward the sea was wiped clean of nearly every structure, while closer to the river, dense construction in a commercial district showed the effects of severe flooding.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The flow depth at the city was just at the level of the second floor, and there were large amounts of debris piled along the streets and in the ground-floor storefronts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In the seaside section of Ulèë Lheuë, the flow depths were over 9 m (30 ft).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Footage showed evidence of back-flowing of the Aceh River, carrying debris and people from destroyed villages at the coast and transporting them up to 40 km (25 mi) inland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A group of small islands: Weh, Breueh, Nasi, Teunom, Bunta, Lumpat, and Batee lie just north of the capital city.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami reached a run-up of 10–20 m (33–66 ft) on the western shorelines of Breueh Island and Nasi Island.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Coastal villages were destroyed by the waves.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On Weh Island, strong surges were experienced in the port of Sabang, yet there was little damage with reported runup values of 3–5 m (9.8–16.4 ft), most likely due to the island being sheltered from the direct attack by the islands to the south-west.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Lhoknga is a small coastal community about 13 km (8.1 mi) south-west of Banda Aceh, located on a flat coastal plain in between two rainforest-covered hills, overlooking a large bay and famous for its large swathe of white sandy beach and surfing activities.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The locals reported 10 to 12 waves, with the second and third being the highest and most destructive.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Interviews with the locals revealed that the sea temporarily receded and exposed coral reefs.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In the distant horizon, gigantic black waves about 30 m (98 ft) high made explosion-like sounds as they broke and approached the shore.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The first wave came rapidly landward from the south-west as a turbulent bore about 0.5–2.5 m (1.6–8.2 ft) high.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The second and third waves were 15–30 m (49–98 ft) high at the coast and appeared like gigantic surfing waves but "taller than the coconut trees and was like a mountain".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The second wave was the largest; it came from the west-southwest within five minutes of the first wave.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami stranded cargo ships, barges and destroyed a cement mining facility near the Lampuuk coast, where it reached the fourth level of the building.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Meulaboh, a remote coastal city, was among the hardest hit by the tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The waves arrived after the sea receded about 500 m (1,600 ft), followed by an advancing small tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The second and third destructive waves arrived later, which exceeded the height of the coconut trees.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The inundation distance is about 5 km (3.1 mi).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Other towns on Aceh's west coast hit by the disaster included Leupung, Lhokruet, Lamno, Patek, Calang, and Teunom.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Affected or destroyed towns on the region's north and east coast were Pidie Regency, Samalanga, Panteraja, and Lhokseumawe.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The high fatality rate in the area was mainly due to lack of preparation of the community towards a tsunami and limited knowledge and education among the population regarding such a natural phenomenon.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Helicopter surveys revealed entire settlements virtually destroyed, with destruction extending miles inland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The greatest run-up height of the tsunami was measured at a hill between Lhoknga and Leupung, on the western coast of the northern tip of Sumatra, near Banda Aceh, and reached 51 m (167 ft).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The island country of Sri Lanka, located about 1,700 km (1,100 mi) from Sumatra, was ravaged by the tsunami around two hours after the earthquake.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami first struck the eastern coastline and subsequently refracted around the southern point of Sri Lanka (Dondra Head).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The refracted tsunami waves then inundated the southwestern part of Sri Lanka after some of its energy was reflected from impact with the Maldives.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Civilian casualties here were second only to those in Indonesia, with approximately 35,000 killed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The eastern shores of the country were the hardest hit since it faced the epicentre of the earthquake, while the southwestern shores were hit later, but the death toll was just as severe.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The southwestern shores are a hotspot for tourists and fishing.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The degradation of the natural environment in Sri Lanka contributed to the high death tolls.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Approximately 90,000 buildings and many wooden houses were destroyed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami arrived on the island as a small brown-orange-coloured flood.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Moments later, the ocean floor was exposed for as much as 1 km (0.62 mi) in places, which was followed by massive second and third waves.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Other videos recorded showed that the tsunami appeared like a flood raging inland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The construction of seawalls and breakwaters reduced the power of waves at some locations.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The largest run-up measured was at 12.5 m (41 ft) with inundation distance of 390–1,500 m (1,280–4,920 ft) in Yala.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Hambantota, run-ups measured 11 m (36 ft) with the greatest inundation distance of 2 km (1.2 mi).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Run-up measurements along the Sri Lankan coasts are at 2.4–4.11 m (7 ft 10 in – 13 ft 6 in).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Waves measured on the east coast ranged from 4.5–9 m (15–30 ft) at Pottuvill to Batticaloa at 2.6–5 m (8 ft 6 in – 16 ft 5 in) in the north-east around Trincomalee and 4–5 m (13–16 ft) in the west coast from Moratuwa to Ambalangoda.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A regular passenger train operating between Maradana and Matara with over 1,750 passengers was derailed and subsequently overturned by the tsunami, claiming at least 1,000 lives in the largest single rail disaster death toll in history.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Estimates based on the state of the shoreline and a high-water mark on a nearby building place the tsunami 7.5–9 m (25–30 ft) above sea level and 2–3 m (6 ft 7 in – 9 ft 10 in) higher than the top of the train.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami travelled eastward through the Andaman Sea and hit the south-western coasts of Thailand, about 2 hours after the earthquake.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Located about 500 km (310 mi) from the epicentre, at the time, the region was popular with tourists because of Christmas.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Many of these tourists were caught off-guard by the tsunami, as they had no prior warning.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Major locations damaged included the western shores of Phuket island, the resort town of Khao Lak in Phang Nga Province, the coastal provinces of Krabi, Satun, Ranong and Trang and small offshore islands like Ko Racha Yai, the Phi Phi islands, the Surin Islands and the Similan archipelago.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Thailand experienced the second largest tsunami run-up.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The province of Phang Nga was the most affected area in Thailand.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The quiet resort town of Khao Lak is located on a stretch of golden sandy beach, famed for its hotels overlooking the Andaman Sea and hilly rainforests.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A video, taken by a local restaurant manager from a hill adjacent to the beach, showed that the tsunami's arrival was preceded by a sudden retreat of the sea exposing the seafloor.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Many tourists and locals can be seen trying to gather fish.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Moments later, the tsunami arrives as a wall of foaming water that slams into the coast, washing away numerous people who had no time to escape.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Another amateur video, captured by a German family at beach level, showed the tsunami appearing as a white horizontal line in the distant horizon, gradually becoming bigger (bore-like), engulfing a jet skier and lifting two police boats.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A maximum inundation of approximately 2 km (1.2 mi) was measured, the inundated depths were 4–7 m (13–23 ft) and there was evidence that the tsunami reached the third floor of a resort hotel.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami in Khao Lak was bigger due to offshore coral reefs and shallow seafloor which caused the tsunami to pile-up.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] This was similar to eyewitness accounts of the tsunami at Banda Aceh.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Khao Lak also experienced the largest tsunami run-up height outside of Sumatra.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The highest-recorded tsunami run-up was measured 19.6 m (64 ft) at Ban Thung Dap, on the south-west tip of Ko Phra Thong Island and the second-highest at 15.8 m (52 ft) at Ban Nam Kim.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Moreover, the largest death toll occurred at Khao Lak, with about 5,000 people killed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In addition, the tsunami inflicted damage to the popular resort town of Ao Nang in Krabi Province.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Video footage showed that the tsunami appeared as multiple white surfs which violently lifted up yachts and boats, eventually crashing onto beaches.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Footage captured at Koh Lanta showed a wall of water swamping the beach, while another video taken at another location showed a large surfing wave-like tsunami approaching the shore, lifting up a yacht and flooding the beach.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] At Koh Sriboya, the tsunami advanced inland as a turbulent medium bore, while at Koh Phayam, Ranong Province, the tsunami appeared as a wall of water.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] At Phuket Province, the island province's western beaches were struck by the tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] At Patong Beach, a popular tourist destination, the tsunami first arrived as a small flood, which swept away cars and surprised people.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] About 10 minutes later, the sea receded for a while before the tsunami arrived again as a large wall of water looming over the skyline and flooding the coast.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Another video from Kamala Beach showed the tsunami flooding the ground floor of a restaurant sweeping away an elderly couple.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On Karon Beach, Kamala Beach and Kata Beach, the tsunami came in like a surging flood inland carrying people and cars.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On some locations, a coastal road, which was built higher than the shore, protected a hotel which was behind it.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On the east coast of Phuket Island, the tsunami height was about 2 m.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In one river mouth, many boats were damaged.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami moved counter-clockwise around Phuket Island, as was the case at Okushiri Island in the 1993 Hokkaido earthquake.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] According to interviews, the second wave was the largest.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami heights were 5–6 m (16–20 ft) and the inundated depth was about 2 m (6.6 ft).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami surprised many tourists at Koh Racha Yai, where it flooded the resorts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] About 250 people perished directly in the tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Phi Phi Islands are a group of small islands that were affected by the tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The north bay of Phi Phi Don Island opens to the north-west in the direction of the tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The measured tsunami height on this beach was 5.8 m (19 ft).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] According to eyewitness accounts, the tsunami came from the north and south.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The ground level was about 2 m above sea level, where there were many cottages and hotels.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The south bay opens to the south-east and faces in the opposite direction from the tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Furthermore, Phi Phi Le Island shields the port of Phi Phi Don Island.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The measured tsunami height was 4.6 m (15 ft) in the port.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Amateur camcorder footage taken by Israeli tourists showed the tsunami advancing inland suddenly as a small flood, gradually becoming more powerful and engulfing the whole beach and resort, with the tsunami carrying a yacht out to sea.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Moreover, the tsunami was detected by scuba divers around offshore islands like the Similan Islands and the Surin Islands.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The divers reported being caught in a violent, swirling current suddenly while underwater.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Local camcorder footage showed the tsunami surging inland and flooding camping equipment at the Similan Islands while the tsunami caught tourists unaware at the Surin Islands, and dragging them out towards the sea.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami reached the states of Andhra Pradesh and Tamil Nadu along the southeastern coastline of the Indian mainland about two hours after the earthquake.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] At the same time, it arrived in the state of Kerala, on the southwestern coast.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There were two to five tsunamis that coincided with the local high tide in some areas.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Along the coast of Tamil Nadu, the 13 km (8.1 mi) Marina Beach in Chennai was battered by the tsunami which swept across the beach taking morning walkers unaware.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Amateur video recorded at a resort beach showed the tsunami arriving as a large wall of water as it approached the coast and flooding it as it advanced inland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Besides that, a 10 m (33 ft) black muddy tsunami ravaged the city of Karaikal, where 492 people died.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The city of Pondicherry, protected by seawalls was relatively unscathed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Local video recorded that before the arrival of the tsunami, people had swarmed the beach to investigate fish that had been stranded on the sand.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Furthermore, at the coastal town of Kanyakumari, the seabed was exposed briefly before a large wall of water can be seen on the horizon and subsequently flooding the town.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Other footage showed the tsunami dramatically crashed into the Vivekananda Rock Memorial.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The worst affected area in Tamil Nadu was Nagapattinam district, with 6,051 fatalities caused by a 5 m (16 ft) tsunami, followed by Cuddalore district, with many villages destroyed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most of the people killed were members of the fishing community.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Velankanni, a coastal town with a Catholic Basilica and a popular pilgrimage destination was also one of the worst hit by the tsunami that struck at around 9.30 am on that Sunday, when pilgrims who were mostly from Kerala among others were inside the church attending the Malayalam Mass.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The rising sea water did not enter the shrine, but the receding waters swept away hundreds of pilgrims who were on the beach.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The shrine's compound, nearby villages, hundreds of shops, homes and pilgrims were washed away into the sea.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Rescue teams extricated more than 400 bodies from the sand and rocks in the vicinity and large number of unidentified bodies were buried in mass graves.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Kerala experienced tsunami-related damage in three southern densely populated districts, Ernakulam, Alappuzha, and Kollam, due to diffraction of the waves around Sri Lanka.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Conversely, the southernmost district of Thiruvananthapuram experienced negligible impact, a result of the wide-angle turn required for diffracted waves to reach the peninsular tip.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The most severe destruction was concentrated along narrow land strips situated between the Arabian Sea to the west and the Kerala backwaters to the east, where the geography restricted inland evacuation.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Initial tidal recession preceded the surge, with the highest fatality rate recorded in the Alappad panchayat—including the villages of Cheriazheekkal and Azheekal—where waves reached heights of 4 m (13 ft) and caused approximately 131 deaths.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Many villages in Andhra Pradesh were destroyed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In the Krishna District, the tsunami created havoc in Manginapudi and on Machalipattanam Beach.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The most affected was Prakasam District, recording 35 deaths, with maximum damage at Singarayakonda.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Given the enormous power of the tsunami, the fishing industry suffered the greatest.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Moreover, the cost of damage in the transport sector was reported in the tens of thousands.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami run-up was only 1.6 m (5.2 ft) in areas of Tamil Nadu shielded by the island of Sri Lanka but was 4–5 m (13–16 ft) in coastal districts such as Nagapattinam in Tamil Nadu directly across from Sumatra.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On the western coast, the runup elevations were 4.5 m (15 ft) at Kanyakumari District in Tamil Nadu and 3.4 m (11 ft) each at Kollam and Ernakulam districts in Kerala.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The time between the waves ranged from about 15 minutes to 90 minutes.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami varied in height from 2 m (6.6 ft) to 10 m (33 ft) based on survivors' accounts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami travelled 2.5 km (1.6 mi) at its maximum inland at Karaikal, Puducherry.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The inundation distance varied between 1,006–500 m (3,301–1,640 ft) in most areas, except at river mouths, where it was more than 1 km (0.62 mi).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Areas with dense coconut groves or mangroves had much smaller inundation distances, and those with river mouths or backwaters saw larger inundation distances.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Presence of seawalls at the Kerala and Tamil Nadu coasts reduced the impact of the waves.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] However, when the seawalls were made of loose stones, the stones were displaced and carried a few metres inland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Due to close proximity to the earthquake, the tsunami took just minutes to devastate the Andaman and Nicobar Islands.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Andaman Islands were moderately affected while the island of Little Andaman and the Nicobar Islands were severely affected by the tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In South Andaman Island, based on local eyewitnesses, there were three tsunami waves, with the third being the most destructive.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Flooding occurred at the coast and low-lying areas inland, which were connected to open sea through creeks.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Inundation was observed, along the east coast of South Andaman Island, restricted to Chidiyatapu, Burmanallah, Kodiaghat, Beadnabad, Corbyn's Cove and Marina Park/Aberdeen Jetty areas.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Several near-shore establishments and numerous infrastructures such as seawalls and a 20 MW diesel-generated power plant at Bamboo Flat were destroyed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] At Port Blair, the water receded before the first wave, and the third wave was the tallest and caused the most damage.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Meanwhile, in the Little Andaman, tsunami waves impinged on the eastern shore about 25 to 30 minutes after the earthquake in a four-wave cycle of which the fourth tsunami was the most devastating with a wave height of about 10 m (33 ft).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami destroyed settlements at Hut Bay within a range of 1 km (0.62 mi) from the seashore.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Run up level up to 3.8 m (12 ft) have been measured.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Malacca, located on the island of Car Nicobar, there were three tsunami waves.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The sea was observed to rise suddenly before the onset of the first wave.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The first wave came 5 minutes after the earthquake, preceded by a recession of the sea up to 600–700 m (2,000–2,300 ft)..
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The second and third waves came in 10-minute intervals after the first wave.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The third wave was the strongest, with a maximum tsunami wave height of 11 m (36 ft).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Waves nearly three stories high devastated the Indian Air Force base, located just south of Malacca.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The maximum tsunami wave height of 11 m (36 ft).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Inundation limit was found to be up to 1.25 km (0.78 mi) inland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The impact of the waves was so severe that four oil tankers were thrown almost 800 m (2,600 ft) from the seashore near Malacca to the Air force colony main gate.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Chuckchucha and Lapati, the tsunami arrived in a three-wave cycle with a maximum tsunami wave height of 12 m (39 ft).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Campbell Bay of Great Nicobar Island, the tsunami waves hit the area three times with an inundation limit of 250–500 m (820–1,640 ft).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A rise in sea level was observed before the first wave came within 5 minutes of the earthquake.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The second and third waves came in 10-minute intervals after the first.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami waves wreaked havoc in the densely populated Jogindar Nagar area, situated 13 km (8.1 mi) south of Campbell Bay.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] According to local accounts, tsunami waves attacked the area three times.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The first wave came five minutes after the mainshock (0629 hrs.) with a marginal drop in sea level.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The second wave came 10 minutes after the first one with a maximum height of 4.8 m (16 ft) to 8 m (26 ft) and caused the major destruction.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The third wave came within 15 minutes after the second with lower wave height.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The maximum inundation limit due to tsunami water was about 500 m (1,600 ft).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The worst affected island in the Andaman and Nicobar chain is Katchall Island, with 303 people confirmed dead and 4,354 missing out of a total population of 5,312.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The significant shielding of Port Blair and Campbell Bay by steep mountainous outcrops contributed to the relatively low wave heights at these locations, whereas the open terrain along the eastern coast at Malacca and Hut Bay contributed to the great height of the tsunami waves.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami severely affected the Maldives at a distance of 2,500 km (1,600 mi) from the epicentre.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Similar to Sri Lanka, survivors reported three waves with the second wave being the most powerful.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Being rich in coral reefs, the Maldives provides an opportunity for scientists to assess the impact of a tsunami on coral atolls.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The significantly lower tsunami impact on the Maldives compared to Sri Lanka is mostly due to the topography and bathymetry of the atoll chain with offshore coral reefs, deep channels separating individual atolls and its arrival within low tide which decreased the power of the tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] After the tsunami, there was some concern that the country might be submerged entirely and become uninhabitable.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The highest tsunami wave measured was 4 m (13 ft) at Vilufushi Island.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami arrived approximately two hours after the earthquake.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The greatest tsunami inundation occurred at North Male Atoll, Male Island at 250 m (820 ft) along the streets.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Local footage recorded showed the tsunami flooding the streets up to knee level in town, while another video taken at the beach showed the tsunami slowly flooding and gradually surging inland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Myanmar, the tsunami caused only moderate damage, which arrived between 2 and 5.5 hours after the earthquake.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Although the country's western Andaman Sea coastline lies at the proximity of the rupture zone, there were smaller tsunamis than the neighbouring Thai coast, because the main tsunami source did not extend to the Andaman Islands.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Another factor is that some coasts of Taninthayi Division were protected by the Myeik Archipelago.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Based on scientific surveys from the Irrawaddy Delta through Taninthayi Division, it was revealed that tsunami heights along the Myanmar coast were between 0.4–2.9 m (1 ft 4 in – 9 ft 6 in).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Eyewitnesses compared the tsunami with the "rainy-season high tide"; although at most locations, the tsunami height was similar or smaller than the "rainy-season high tide" level.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Interviews with residents indicate that they did not feel the earthquake in Taninthayi Division or the Irrawaddy Delta.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The 71 casualties can be attributed to poor housing infrastructure and additionally, the fact that the coastal residents in the surveyed areas live on flat land along the coast, especially in the Irrawaddy Delta, and that there is no higher ground to which to evacuate.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami heights from the earthquake were not more than 3 m (9.8 ft) along the Myanmar coast, the amplitudes were slightly large off the Irrawaddy Delta, probably because the shallow delta caused a concentration in tsunami energy.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami travelled 5,000 km (3,100 mi) west across the open ocean before striking the East African country of Somalia.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Around 289 fatalities were reported in the Horn of Africa, drowned by four tsunami waves.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The hardest-hit was a 650 km (400 mi) stretch of coastline between Garacad (Mudug region) and Hafun (Bari region), which forms part of Puntland province.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most of the victims were reported along the low-lying Xaafuun Peninsula.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Puntland coast in northern Somalia was by far the area hardest hit by the waves to the west of the Indian subcontinent.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The waves arrived around noon local time.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Consequently, tsunami runup heights vary from 5 m (16 ft) to 9 m (30 ft) with inundation distances varying from 44 m (144 ft) to 704 m (2,310 ft).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The maximum runup height of almost 9 m (30 ft) was recorded in Bandarbeyla.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] An even higher runup point was measured on a cliff near the town of Eyl, solely on an eyewitness account.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The highest death toll was in Hafun, with 19 dead and 160 people presumed missing out of its 5,000 inhabitants.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] This was the highest number of casualties in a single African town and the largest tsunami death toll in a single town to the west of the Indian subcontinent.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Small drawbacks were observed before the third and most powerful tsunami wave flooded the town.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami also reached Malaysia, mainly on the northern states such as Kedah, Perak and Penang and on offshore islands such as Langkawi island.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Peninsular Malaysia was shielded by the full force of the tsunami due to the protection offered by the island of Sumatra, which lies just off the western coast.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Bangladesh escaped major damage and deaths because the water displaced by the strike-slip fault was relatively little on the northern section of the rupture zone, which ruptured slowly.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Yemen, the tsunami killed two people with a maximum runup of 2 m (6.6 ft).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami was detected in the southern parts of east Africa, where rough seas were reported, specifically on the eastern and southern coasts that face the Indian Ocean.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A few other African countries also recorded fatalities; one in Kenya, three in Seychelles, ten in Tanzania, and South Africa, where two were killed as a direct result of the tsunami—the furthest from the epicentre.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tidal surges also occurred along the Western Australian coast that lasted for several hours, resulting in boats losing their moorings and two people needing to be rescued.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] According to the final report of the Tsunami Evaluation Coalition, a total of 227,898 people died.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Another common total, as given by the UN Office of the Special Envoy for Tsunami Recovery, is 229,866 dead.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Measured in lives lost, this is one of the ten worst earthquakes in recorded history, as well as the single worst tsunami in history.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Indonesia was the worst affected area, with most death toll estimates at around 170,000.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The death toll for Indonesia alone may be as high as 172,761 lives.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] An initial report by Siti Fadilah Supari, the Indonesian Minister of Health at the time, estimated the death total to be as high as 220,000 in Indonesia alone, giving a total of 280,000 fatalities.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] However, the estimated number of dead and missing in Indonesia were later reduced by over 50,000.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In their report, the Tsunami Evaluation Coalition stated, "It should be remembered that all such data are subject to error, as data on missing persons especially are not always as good as one might wish".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] A much higher number of deaths has been suggested for Myanmar based on reports from Thailand.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The tsunami caused severe damage and deaths as far as the east coast of Africa, with the furthest recorded fatality directly attributed to the tsunami at Rooi-Els, close to Cape Town, 8,000 km (5,000 mi) from the epicentre.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Relief agencies reported that one third of the dead appeared to be children.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] This was a result of the high proportion of children in the populations of many of the affected regions and because children were the least able to resist being overcome by the surging waters.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Oxfam went on to report that as many as four times more women than men were killed in some regions because they were waiting on the beach for the fishers to return and looking after their children in the houses.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] States of emergency were declared in Sri Lanka, Indonesia, and the Maldives.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The United Nations estimated at the outset that the relief operation would be the costliest in human history.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Then-UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan stated that reconstruction would probably take between five and ten years.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Governments and non-governmental organizations feared that the final death toll might double as a result of diseases, prompting a massive humanitarian response.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In addition to a large number of local residents, up to 9,000 foreign tourists (mostly Europeans) enjoying the peak holiday travel season were among the dead or missing, especially people from the Nordic countries.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Sweden was the European country most severely affected both in absolute numbers, and by a wide margin when considered in relation to the country's population, with a death toll of 543.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] France was close behind with a death toll of 542 followed by Germany with 539 identified victims.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Beyond the heavy toll on human lives, the Indian Ocean earthquake caused an enormous environmental impact that affected the region for many years.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Severe damage was inflicted on ecosystems such as mangroves, coral reefs, forests, coastal wetlands, vegetation, sand dunes and rock formations, animal and plant biodiversity and groundwater.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Also, the spread of solid and liquid waste and industrial chemicals, water pollution and the destruction of sewage collectors and treatment plants threatened the environment even further.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The environmental impact took a long time and significant resources to assess.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The main effect was caused by poisoning of the freshwater supplies and of the soil by saltwater infiltration and a deposit of a salt layer over arable land.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In the Maldives, 16 to 17 coral reef atolls that were overcome by sea waves are without fresh water and could be rendered uninhabitable for decades.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Uncountable wells that served communities were invaded by sea, sand, and earth, and aquifers were invaded through porous rock.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] On the island's east coast, the tsunami contaminated wells on which many villagers relied for drinking water.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Colombo-based International Water Management Institute monitored the effects of saltwater and concluded that the wells recovered to pre-tsunami drinking water quality one-and-a-half years after the event.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The IWMI developed protocols for cleaning wells contaminated by saltwater; these were subsequently officially endorsed by the World Health Organization as part of its series of Emergency Guidelines.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Salted-over soil becomes infertile, and it is difficult and costly to restore for agriculture.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] It also causes the death of plants and important soil micro-organisms.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Thousands of rice, mango, and banana plantations in Sri Lanka were destroyed almost entirely and will take years to recover.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In addition to other forms of aid, the Australian government sent ecological experts to help develop strategies for reef-monitoring and rehabilitation of marine environments and coral reefs in the Maldives, Seychelles and other areas.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Scientists had developed significant ecological expertise from work with the Great Barrier Reef, in Australia's northeastern waters.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In response to the unprecedented situation, the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) worked with governments in the region to determine the severity of the ecological impact and how to address it.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] UNEP established an emergency fund, set up a Task Force to respond to requests for assistance from countries affected by the tsunami, and was able to mobilize and distribute approximately US$9.3 million for environmental recovery and disaster risk reduction between 2004 and 2007.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Funding came from other international agencies and from countries including Finland, Norway, Spain, Sweden and the United Kingdom.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Evidence suggested that the presence of mangroves in coastal areas had provided some protection, when compared to areas that had been cleared for aquaculture or development.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] As a result, mangrove restoration become a focus of a number of projects, with varied success.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Such approaches to ecosystem-based disaster risk reduction appear to be most successful when local communities are closely involved as stakeholders throughout the process, and when careful attention is paid to the physical conditions of chosen sites to ensure that mangroves can thrive there.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The level of damage to the economy resulting from the tsunami depends on the scale examined.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] While the overall impact on the national economies was minor, local economies were devastated.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The two main occupations most affected by the tsunami were fishing and tourism.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Some economists believe that damage to the affected national economies will be minor because losses in the tourism and fishing industries are a relatively small percentage of the GDP.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] However, others caution that damage to infrastructure is an overriding factor.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In some areas drinking water supplies and farm fields may have been contaminated for years by saltwater from the ocean.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The impact on coastal fishing communities and the people living there, some of the poorest in the region, has been devastating with high losses of income earners as well as boats and fishing gear.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In Sri Lanka, artisanal fishery, in which the use of fish baskets, fishing traps, and spears are commonly used, is an important source of fish for local markets; industrial fishery is the major economic activity, providing direct employment to about 250,000 people.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In recent years the fishery industry has emerged as a dynamic export-oriented sector, generating substantial foreign exchange earnings.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Preliminary estimates indicated that 66% of the fishing fleet and industrial infrastructure in coastal regions were destroyed by the wave surges.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] While the tsunami destroyed many of the boats vital to Sri Lanka's fishing industry, it also created a demand for fibreglass-reinforced plastic catamarans in the boatyards of Tamil Nadu.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Given that over 51,000 vessels were lost to the tsunami, the industry boomed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] However, the huge demand has led to lower quality in the process, and some important materials were sacrificed to cut prices for those who were impoverished by the tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Even though only coastal regions were directly affected by the waters of the tsunami, the indirect effects have spread to inland provinces as well.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Since the media coverage of the event was so extensive, many tourists cancelled vacations and trips to that part of the world, even though their travel destinations may not have been affected.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] This ripple effect could especially be felt in the inland provinces of Thailand, such as Krabi, which acted as a starting point for many other tourist destinations in Thailand.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Countries in the region appealed to tourists to return, pointing out that most tourist infrastructure is undamaged.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] However, tourists were reluctant to do so for psychological reasons.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Even beach resorts in parts of Thailand which were untouched by the tsunami were hit by cancellations.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Both the earthquake and the tsunami may have affected shipping in the Malacca Straits, which separate Malaysia and the Indonesian island of Sumatra, by changing the depth of the seabed and by disturbing navigational buoys and old shipwrecks.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In one area of the Strait, water depths were previously up to 1,200 m (4,000 ft), and are now only 30 m (100 ft) in some areas, making shipping impossible and dangerous.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] These problems also made the delivery of relief aid more challenging.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Compiling new navigational charts may take months or years.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Officials also hoped that piracy in the region would drop off, since the tsunami had killed pirates and destroyed their boats.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Due to multiple factors, there was a 71.6% drop in the number of piracy incidents between 2004 and 2005, from 60 to 17 incidents.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Levels remained relatively low for some years.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] However, between 2013 and 2014, piracy incidents rose dramatically by 73.2% to exceed pre-tsunami levels.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The last major tsunami in the Indian Ocean was about A.D.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In 2008, a team of scientists working on Phra Thong, a barrier island along the hard-hit west coast of Thailand, reported evidence of at least three previous major tsunamis in the preceding 2,800 years, the most recent from about 700 years ago.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The 2004 earthquake and tsunami combined is the world's deadliest natural disaster since the 1976 Tangshan earthquake.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The earthquake was the third-most-powerful earthquake recorded since 1900.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The deadliest-known earthquake in history occurred in 1556 in Shaanxi, China, with an estimated death toll of 830,000, though figures from this period may not be as reliable.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Before 2004, the tsunami created in both Indian and Pacific Ocean waters by the 1883 eruption of Krakatoa, thought to have resulted in anywhere from 36,000 to 120,000 deaths, had probably been the deadliest in the region.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In 1782, about 40,000 people are thought to have been killed by a tsunami (or a cyclone) in the South China Sea.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The deadliest tsunami before 2004 was Italy's 1908 Messina earthquake on the Mediterranean Sea where the earthquake and tsunami killed about 123,000.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Many health professionals and aid workers have reported widespread psychological trauma associated with the tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Even 14 years afterwards, researchers find HPA axis dysregulation and "burnout" in survivors.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Traditional beliefs in many of the affected regions state that a relative of the family must bury the body of the dead, and in many cases, no body remained to be buried.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The hardest-hit area, Aceh, is a religiously conservative Islamic society and has had no tourism nor any Western presence in recent years due to the insurgency between the Indonesian military and Free Aceh Movement (GAM).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Some believe that the tsunami was divine punishment for lay Muslims shirking their daily prayers or following a materialistic lifestyle.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Others have said that Allah was angry that Muslims were killing each other in an ongoing conflict.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Saudi cleric Muhammad Al-Munajjid attributed it to divine retribution against non-Muslim vacationers "who used to sprawl all over the beaches and in pubs overflowing with wine" during Christmas break.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The widespread devastation caused by the tsunami led GAM to declare a cease-fire on 28 December 2004 followed by the Indonesian government, and the two groups resumed long-stalled peace talks, which resulted in a peace agreement signed 15 August 2005.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The agreement explicitly cites the tsunami as a justification.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In a poll conducted in 27 countries, 15% of respondents named the tsunami the most significant event of the year.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Only the Iraq War was named by as many respondents.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The extensive international media coverage of the tsunami, and the role of mass media and journalists in reconstruction, were discussed by editors of newspapers and broadcast media in tsunami-affected areas, in special video-conferences set up by the Asia Pacific Journalism Centre.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The tsunami left both the people and government of India in a state of heightened alert.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] On 30 December 2004, four days after the tsunami, Terra Research notified the India government that its sensors indicated there was a possibility of 7.9 to 8.1 magnitude tectonic shift in the next 12 hours between Sumatra and New Zealand.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In response, the Indian Minister of Home Affairs announced that a fresh onslaught of deadly tsunami was likely along the southern Indian coast and the Andaman and Nicobar Islands, even as there was no sign of turbulence in the region.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The announcement generated panic in the Indian Ocean region and caused thousands to flee their homes, which resulted in jammed roads.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The announcement was a false alarm, and the Home Affairs minister withdrew their announcement.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] On further investigation, the India government learned that the consulting company Terra Research was run from the home of a self-described earthquake forecaster who had no telephone listing and maintained a website where he sold copies of his detection system.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The tsunami had a severe humanitarian and political impact in Sweden.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The hardest-hit country outside Asia, it lost 543 tourists in the disaster, mainly in Thailand.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Persson Cabinet was heavily criticized for its inaction.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Smith Dharmasaroja, a meteorologist who had predicted that an earthquake and tsunami "is going to occur for sure" in 1994, was assigned the development of the Thai tsunami warning system.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Indian Ocean Tsunami Warning System was formed in early 2005 to provide an early warning of tsunamis for inhabitants around the Indian Ocean coasts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The changes in the distribution of masses inside the Earth due to the earthquake had several consequences.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] It displaced the North Pole by 25 mm (0.98 in).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] It also slightly changed the shape of the Earth, specifically by decreasing Earth's oblateness by about one part in 10 billion, consequentially increasing Earth's rotation a little and thus shortening the length of the day by 2.68 microseconds.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Indian Ocean Tsunami Archives were added to the UNESCO Memory of the World register in 2017.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The archive consists of video, audio, and photographs.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] A great deal of humanitarian aid was needed because of widespread damage to the infrastructure, shortages of food and water, and economic damage.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Epidemics were of particular concern due to the high population density and tropical climate of the affected areas.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The main concern of humanitarian and government agencies was to provide sanitation facilities and fresh drinking water to contain the spread of diseases such as cholera, diphtheria, dysentery, typhoid and hepatitis A and hepatitis B.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] There was also a great concern that the death toll could increase as disease and hunger spread.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] However, because of the initial quick response, this was minimized.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In the days following the tsunami, significant effort was spent in burying bodies hurriedly due to fear of disease spreading.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] However, the public health risks may have been exaggerated, and therefore this may not have been the best way to allocate resources.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The World Food Programme provided food aid to more than 1.3 million people affected by the tsunami.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Also, Italy offered US$95 million, increased later to US$113 million of which US$42 million was donated by the population using the SMS system.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Australia, India, Japan and the United States formed an ad-hoc corroborative group, and it was the origin of the Quadrilateral Security Dialogue.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] According to USAID, the US has pledged additional funds in long-term U.S. support to help the tsunami victims rebuild their lives.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Bush asked Congress to increase the U.S. commitment to a total of US$950 million.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Officials estimated that billions of dollars would be needed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Bush also asked his father, former president George H.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Bush, and former president Bill Clinton to lead a U.S. effort to provide private aid to the tsunami victims.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In mid-March, the Asian Development Bank reported that over US$4 billion in aid promised by governments was behind schedule.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Sri Lanka reported that it had received no foreign government aid, while foreign individuals had been generous.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Many charities were given considerable donations from the public.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] For example, in the United Kingdom, the public donated roughly £330 million sterling (nearly US$600 million).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] This considerably outweighed the allocation by the government to disaster relief and reconstruction of £75 million and came to an average of about £5.50 (US$10) donated by every citizen.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2004-indian-ocean-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In August 2006, fifteen local aid staff working on post-tsunami rebuilding were found executed in north-east Sri Lanka after heavy fighting between government troops and the Tamil Tiger rebels, the main umbrella body for aid agencies in the country said.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] A State Opening of the Parliament of the United Kingdom took place on 17 July 2024 when King Charles III opened the first session of the Parliament elected in 2024, which was the first after the 2024 general election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Charles III delivered the King's Speech, his second as monarch, and the first since returning to his public duties after receiving treatment for cancer earlier in the year.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] The King set out the UK government's legislative programme for the following parliamentary session.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Along with Queen Camilla, Charles III travelled to Westminster in the Diamond Jubilee State Coach and was accompanied by the Household Cavalry.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] At Westminster, the King read the 1,421 word speech from the throne in the House of Lords.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] The speech was then debated by both Houses of Parliament.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] July 2024 marked Keir Starmer's first State Opening of Parliament since becoming UK Prime Minister after the Labour Party won the election earlier that month.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] On 30 May 2024, and following the announcement of the 2024 general election, it was announced that there would be a State Opening of Parliament on 17 July.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] The election, held on 4 July, was won by the Labour Party, which defeated the incumbent Conservative government after 14 years in office, securing a landslide victory, with Sir Keir Starmer becoming prime minister.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] The preceding government's tenure had seen high inflation, political scandals and an economic crisis, and Starmer's election campaign had focussed on improving the UK's economy and infrastructure while not raising personal taxes.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] He was keen to change the direction of the country with a raft of new legislation.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] It was Charles III's second State Opening of Parliament since his accession to the throne in September 2022, and his first since returning to his public duties after being diagnosed with cancer in February 2024, and subsequently receiving treatment for the illness.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Although the King had stepped back from his public duties for a time, he had continued with his constitutional role, such as private meetings, including those with the prime minister, and paperwork.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] On the morning of the State Opening, the Metropolitan Police arrested 10 members of the protest group Youth Demand after the organisation stated its intention to disrupt proceedings over Keir Starmer's handling of the Gaza war.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] The individuals were detained on suspicion of conspiracy to cause public nuisance.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] On the morning of 17 July, Samantha Dixon MP, as Vice-Chamberlain of the Household, was "taken hostage" at Buckingham Palace to ensure the King's safe return from Parliament.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Charles III and Queen Camilla then travelled from Buckingham Palace to Westminster in the Diamond Jubilee State Coach, escorted by the Household Cavalry.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] The route was lined with military personnel, including members of the Grenadier Guards, Irish Guards and Coldstream Guards, as well as members of the RAF and Royal Navy.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] The King and Queen entered the Palace of Westminster through the Sovereign's Entrance, reserved exclusively for the monarch, and changed into the Robes of State, before proceeding to the House of Lords, where the King would read the speech from the throne.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] MPs from the House of Commons were summoned to attend the Lords by Sarah Clarke, who holds the office of Black Rod.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] As a symbol of the House of Commons' independence from the reigning monarch, the doors to the chamber were closed upon Clarke's approach, requiring her to knock three times for it to be opened.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Once MPs had assembled in the Lords, Charles III then read the King's Speech.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] The speech, prepared by the UK government, set out its planned programme of legislation for the next session of parliament, and was read by the King in a neutral tone so as not to show any appearance of political support.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] MPs listened to the speech in silence, before returning to the Commons, where a debate on the speech began two hours or so later.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] At 1,421 words, it was the longest monarch's speech to be delivered to Parliament since 2003.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] The occasion also coincided with the Queen's 77th birthday.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] The twelve minute speech included 39 pieces of legislation that Labour hoped to pass during the forthcoming parliamentary session, with a focus on helping to improve economic growth.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Chief among these were plans to change planning rules in order to facilitate the building of housing and infrastructure.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Plans were also announced to renationalise the railways, strengthen the rights of employees, devolve powers to regional mayors, tackle illegal immigration and reform the House of Lords.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] In addition, a number of bills proposed by the previous Conservative administration were also included, notably the Tobacco and Vapes Bill, which had appeared in the 2023 King's Speech, but had been abandoned after the election was called.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] However, Labour's election manifesto pledges to reduce the UK voting age from 18 to 16 was absent from the programme.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Speaking about the voting age, Lucy Powell, the Leader of the House of Commons, told the BBC it remained a government commitment and that she hoped the age would be lowered by the time of the next general election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Starmer had also faced pressure from some of his own MPs, as well as the Scottish National Party, to scrap the two-child benefit cap, but this was also not included.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Responding to the speech, Leader of the Opposition and Leader of the Conservative Party Rishi Sunak said his party would not oppose the government "for the sake of it", but would hold them to account on their election promises.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] On proposals to change planning laws, he said that though such changes were needed "a system that does not allow local people to have a say will damage public consent for more housing in the long term".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Daisy Cooper, the deputy leader of the Liberal Democrats, welcomed the proposals on Mental Health Act but called for greater ambition on health and social care.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Stephen Gethins of the Scottish National Party, called for the government to reverse the "hard Tory Brexit" arguing it was "the biggest thing pulling back growth", and criticised the government for not removing the two-child benefit cap.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Richard Tice, deputy leader of Reform UK, argued Labour's plans would increase tax and lead to greater regulation.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Green Party MP Ellie Chowns called for "bolder action" on building regulations and rent controls.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Writing in *The Guardian*, Martin Kettle argued that in his first King's Speech, Starmer was taking a long term approach: "trying to balance impatience for change with the inevitability that the process will be gradual".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] BBC economics editor Faisal Islam suggested that it would "take well into next year before we see any impact on economic growth from these plans".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] The BBC's Ben Chu observed that a number of challenges inherited from the previous government had not been addressed in the speech, including public sector pay, which would need to be addressed by the end of July when the public sector pay review for the 2024–25 financial year must be concluded.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Failure to do so, he argued, could make government plans to recruit more nurses and teachers more difficult, and even risk further strikes.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Plans to renationalise the railways were welcomed by rail unions, who said the industry would be "run as a public service, not for private profit", with Mick Whelan, the general secretary of ASLEF, describing it as "the right decision, at the right time".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] However, the plans were viewed less favourably by the UK's 14 train operators.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Andy Bagnall, chief executive of their umbrella organisation, Rail Partners, described the establishment of Great British Railways as "an important milestone", but said "Full nationalisation is a political not a practical solution, which will increase costs over time".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] On the same day the King's Speech was delivered, Starmer announced the establishment of a child poverty task force to investigate how best to support the estimated four million children living in poverty, a figure which was said to have increased by 700,000 since 2010.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Skills England, a body whose objective will be to reduce the need for overseas employees by improving skills training for people in England, was launched on 22 July.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] Former prime minister Liz Truss wrote a letter of complaint to Cabinet Secretary Simon Case over a reference to her September 2022 mini-budget as being "disastrous".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-state-opening-of-parliament] The term was removed after she described it as untrue, and a "flagrant breach" of the civil service code.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on 4 July 2024 to elect all 650 members of the House of Commons.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The opposition Labour Party, led by Keir Starmer, won a landslide victory over the governing Conservative Party under Prime Minister Rishi Sunak, ending 14 years of Conservative-led government.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour secured 411 seats and a 172-seat majority, the third-best showing in the party's history and its best since 2001.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The party's vote share was 33.7%, the lowest of any governing party on record, making this the least proportional general election in British history.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They became the largest party in England, Scotland and Wales.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives suffered their worst-ever defeat, winning 121 seats with 23.7% of the vote and losing 251 seats, including those of the former prime minister Liz Truss and 12 cabinet ministers.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A total of 335 new MPs entered the House of Commons.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Smaller parties saw record support, with 42.6% of the total vote.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats, led by Ed Davey, became the third-largest party with 72 seats, their best result ever and better than any Liberal Party result since 1923.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Reform UK, led by Nigel Farage, won five seats and 14.3% of the vote, the third-highest vote share, and the Green Party won four seats.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] For both parties this was their best parliamentary result to date.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In Scotland, the Scottish National Party (SNP) dropped from 48 to nine seats, losing its status as Scotland's largest party.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In Northern Ireland, which has a distinct set of political parties, Sinn Féin retained seven seats, while the Democratic Unionist Party dropped from eight to five seats, making this the first election in which an Irish nationalist party won the most seats in Northern Ireland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Campaign issues included the economy, healthcare, housing, energy and immigration.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] There was relatively little discussion of Brexit, which was a major issue during the 2019 general election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This was the first general election under the Dissolution and Calling of Parliament Act 2022, the first with photo identification required to vote in Great Britain, and the first contested using the new constituency boundaries implemented following the 2023 review of Westminster constituencies.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservative Party under Boris Johnson won a large majority at the 2019 general election and the new government passed the Brexit withdrawal agreement.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The COVID-19 pandemic saw the government institute extensive public health restrictions, including limitations on social interaction, that Johnson and some of his staff were later found to have broken.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The resulting political scandal (Partygate), one of many controversies during Johnson's premiership, saw the Conservatives lose their poll lead.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] These scandals culminated in the resignation of over 50 ministers from the Government following allegations of sexual misconduct against a government minister.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Johnson announced his resignation in July 2022, to become effective from the election of a successor.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] He resigned as MP the following year, after an investigation unanimously found that he had lied to Parliament.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Liz Truss won the resultant leadership election and succeeded Johnson.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Truss announced large-scale tax cuts and borrowing in a mini-budget on 23 September, although many of its measures were reversed following financial instability.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] She resigned in October, making her the shortest-serving prime minister in British history, and was succeeded unopposed by Rishi Sunak.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] During his premiership, Sunak was credited with improving the economy and stabilising national politics following the premierships of his predecessors, although many of his pledges and policy announcements ultimately went unfulfilled.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] He did not avert further unpopularity for the Conservatives who, by the time of Sunak's election, had been in government for 12 years.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Public opinion in favour of a change in government was reflected in the Conservatives' poor performance at the 2022, 2023 and 2024 local elections.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Keir Starmer won the Labour Party's 2020 leadership election, succeeding Jeremy Corbyn.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Starmer repositioned the party away from the left and toward the political centre, and emphasised the elimination of antisemitism within the party.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Starmer's leading his party rightward in order to improve its electability has been widely compared to Tony Blair's development of New Labour in the 1990s.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The political turmoil from the Conservative scandals and government crises led to Labour having a significant lead in polling over the Conservatives, often by very wide margins, since late 2021, coinciding with the start of the Partygate scandal.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour made gains in local elections: in the 2023 local elections, Labour gained more than 500 councillors and 22 councils, becoming the largest party in local government for the first time since 2002.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Ed Davey, who previously served in the Cameron–Clegg coalition, won the Liberal Democrats' 2020 leadership election, succeeding Jo Swinson, who lost her seat in the previous general election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Davey prioritised defeating the Conservatives and ruled out working with them following the election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats made gains in local elections: in the 2024 local elections, the Liberal Democrats finished second for the first time in a local election cycle since 2009.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Like the Conservatives, the SNP suffered political turmoil and saw a decrease in their popularity in opinion polling, with multiple party leaders and First Ministers (Nicola Sturgeon, Humza Yousaf and John Swinney) and the Operation Branchform police investigation.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Sturgeon claimed occupational burnout was the reason for her resignation, while Yousaf resigned amid a government crisis following his termination of a power-sharing agreement with the Scottish Greens.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] When Swinney assumed the leadership after being elected unopposed to succeed Yousaf, the SNP had been in government for 17 years.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Carla Denyer and Adrian Ramsay took over leadership of the Green Party of England and Wales from Siân Berry and Jonathan Bartley in 2021.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Rhun ap Iorwerth took over leadership of Plaid Cymru.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Brexit Party rebranded as Reform UK, and was initially led by Richard Tice in the years preceding the election before Nigel Farage resumed leadership during the election campaign.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Edwin Poots took over as the Democratic Unionist Party leader in May 2021 but lasted only 20 days.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] He was replaced by Jeffrey Donaldson, who resigned in March 2024 after being arrested on charges relating to historical sex offences.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] He appeared in court on 3 July, the day before polling day, to face additional sex offence charges.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Gavin Robinson initially took over as interim leader, and then became the permanent leader in May.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This table relates to the composition of the House of Commons at the 2019 general election and its dissolution on 30 May 2024 and summarises the changes in party affiliation that took place during the 2019–2024 Parliament.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Originally, the next election was scheduled to take place on 2 May 2024 under the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] At the 2019 general election, in which the Conservatives won a majority of 80 seats, the party's manifesto contained a commitment to repeal the Fixed-term Parliaments Act.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In December 2020, the government duly published a draft Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011 (Repeal) Bill, later retitled the Dissolution and Calling of Parliament Act 2022.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This entered into force on 24 March 2022.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Thus, the prime minister can again request the monarch to dissolve Parliament and call an early election with 25 working days' notice.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Section 4 of the Act provided: "If it has not been dissolved earlier, a Parliament dissolves at the beginning of the day that is the fifth anniversary of the day on which it first met".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Electoral Commission confirmed that the 2019 Parliament would, therefore, have to be dissolved, at the latest, by 17 December 2024, and that the next general election had to take place no later than 28 January 2025.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] With no election date fixed in law, there was speculation as to when the prime minister, Rishi Sunak, would call an election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 18 December 2023, Sunak told journalists that the election would take place in 2024 rather than January 2025.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 4 January, he first suggested the general election would probably be in the second half of 2024.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Throughout 2024, political commentators and MPs expected the election to be held in the autumn.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 22 May 2024, following much speculation through the day (including being asked about it by Stephen Flynn at Prime Minister's Questions), Sunak officially announced the election would be held on 4 July with the dissolution of the Parliament on 30 May.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The deadline for candidate nominations was 7 June 2024, with political campaigning for four weeks until polling day on 4 July.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On the day of the election, polling stations across the country were open from 7 am, and closed at 10 pm.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The date chosen for the 2024 general election made it the first to be held in July since the 1945 general election almost exactly seventy-nine years earlier.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A total of 4,515 candidates were nominated, more than in any previous general election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] General elections in the United Kingdom are organised using first-past-the-post voting.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservative Party, which won a majority at the 2019 general election, included pledges in its manifesto to remove the 15-year limit on voting for British citizens living abroad, and to introduce a voter identification requirement in Great Britain.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] These changes were included in the Elections Act 2022.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies, which proposed reducing the number of constituencies from 650 to 600, commenced in 2011 but was paused in January 2013.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Following the 2015 general election, each of the four parliamentary boundary commissions of the United Kingdom recommenced their review process in April 2016.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The four commissions submitted their final recommendations to the Secretary of State on 5 September 2018 and made their reports public a week later.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, the proposals were never put forward for approval before the calling of the general election held on 12 December 2019, and in December 2020 the reviews were formally abandoned under the Schedule to the Parliamentary Constituencies Act 2020.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A projection by psephologists Colin Rallings and Michael Thrasher of how the 2017 votes would have translated to seats under the 2018 boundaries suggested the changes would have been beneficial to the Conservatives and detrimental to Labour.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In March 2020, Cabinet Office minister Chloe Smith confirmed that the 2023 review of Westminster constituencies would be based on retaining 650 seats.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The previous relevant legislation was amended by the Parliamentary Constituencies Act 2020 and the four boundary commissions formally launched their 2023 reviews on 5 January 2021.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They were required to issue their final reports prior to 1 July 2023.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Once the reports had been laid before Parliament, Orders in Council giving effect to the final proposals had to be made within four months, unless "there are exceptional circumstances".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Prior to the Parliamentary Constituencies Act 2020, boundary changes could not be implemented until they were approved by both Houses of Parliament.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The boundary changes were approved at a meeting of the Privy Council on 15 November 2023 and came into force on 29 November 2023, meaning that the election was contested on these new boundaries.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The election was contested under new constituency boundaries established by the 2023 review of Westminster constituencies.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Consequently, media outlets reported seat gains and losses as compared to notional results.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] These are estimates of the results if all votes cast in 2019 were unchanged, but regrouped by the new constituency boundaries.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Since notional results in the vote counts at parliamentary elections in the UK do not yield figures at any level more specific than that of the whole constituency, it is only possible to estimate the notional results, with the assistance of local election results.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In England, seats were redistributed towards Southern England, away from Northern England, due to the different rates of population growth.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] North West England and North East England lost two seats each, whereas South East England gained seven and South West England gained three.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Based on historical voting patterns, this was expected to help the Conservatives.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Using the new boundaries, different parties would have won several constituencies with unchanged names but changed boundaries from the 2019 election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] For example, the Conservatives would have won Wirral West and Leeds North West instead of the Labour Party, but Labour would have won Pudsey and Heywood & Middleton instead of the Conservatives.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Westmorland and Lonsdale, the constituency represented by former Liberal Democrat leader Tim Farron, was notionally a Conservative seat.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In Scotland, 57 MPs were elected, down from the 59 in 2019, with the following notional partisan composition of Scotland's parliamentary delegation.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The SNP would have remained steady on 48 seats despite two of its constituencies being dissolved.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Scottish Conservatives' seat count of six would likewise remained unchanged.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Scottish Labour would have retained Edinburgh South, the sole constituency they won in 2019.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Under the new boundaries, Wales lost eight seats, electing 32 MPs instead of the 40 it elected in 2019.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Welsh Labour would have won 18 instead of the 22 MPs it elected in 2019, and the Welsh Conservatives 12 instead of 14.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Due to the abolition and merging of rural constituencies in West Wales, Plaid Cymru would have only won two seats instead of four.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Nonetheless, the boundary changes were expected to cause difficulty for the Conservatives as more pro-Labour areas were added to some of their strongest seats.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In Northern Ireland, the notional results are identical to the actual results of the 2019 general election in Northern Ireland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour entered the election with a large lead over the Conservatives in opinion polls, and the potential scale of the party's victory was a topic of discussion during the campaign period.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The economy, healthcare, education, infrastructure development, environment, housing, energy, and immigration, and standards in public office were main campaign topics.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservative campaign led by Rishi Sunak focused primarily on attacks towards Labour over alleged tax plans including a – robustly disputed – claim that Labour would cost households £2,000 more in tax.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Keir Starmer used the word "change" as his campaign slogan and offered voters the chance to "turn the page" by voting Labour.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrat campaign led by Ed Davey was dominated by his campaign stunts, which were used to bring attention to campaign topics.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On the afternoon of 22 May 2024, Sunak announced that he had asked the King to call a general election for 4 July 2024, surprising his own MPs.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The calling of the election was welcomed by all major parties.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Sunak's announcement took place during heavy rain at a lectern outside 10 Downing Street, without the use of any shelter from the downpour.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The D:Ream song "Things Can Only Get Better" (previously used by the Labour Party in its successful 1997 general election campaign) was being played loudly in the background by the political activist Steve Bray as Sunak announced the date of the general election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This led to the song reaching number two on UK's iTunes Charts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] At the beginning of the campaign, Labour had a significant lead in polling over the Conservatives.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Polling also showed Labour doing well against the SNP in Scotland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] When visiting Windermere, Davey fell off a paddleboard, while campaigning to highlight the issue of sewage discharges into rivers and lakes.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A couple of days later, Davey won media attention when going down a Slip 'N Slide, while drawing attention to deteriorating mental health among children.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 23 May, Sunak said that before the election there would be no flights to Rwanda for those seeking asylum.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Immigration figures were published for 2023 showing immigration remained at historically high levels, but had fallen compared to 2022.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Nigel Farage announced that he would not be standing in the general election, preferring to focus on campaigning for the 2024 United States presidential election instead.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, Farage later announced on 3 June that, contrary to his statement earlier in the campaign, he would stand for Parliament in Clacton, and that he had resumed leadership of Reform UK, taking over from Richard Tice, who remained the party's chairman.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The SNP campaign launch the same day was overshadowed by a dispute around leader John Swinney's support for embattled MSP Michael Matheson and developments in Operation Branchform, the investigation into potential misuse of campaign funds by Nicola Sturgeon and her husband.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Starmer launched the Labour Party campaign in Gillingham at the Priestfield Stadium.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 24 May, the Conservatives proposed setting up a Royal Commission to consider a form of mandatory national service.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It would be made up of two streams for 18-year-olds to choose from, either 'community volunteering' by volunteering with organisations such as the NHS, fire service, ambulance, search and rescue, and critical local infrastructure, or 'military training' in areas like logistics and cyber security.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Former Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn announced on 24 May he was standing as an independent in Islington North against a Labour candidate, and was thus expelled from the party.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 27 May, Starmer made a keynote speech on security and other issues.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 28 May, the Conservatives pledged a "Triple Lock Plus" where the personal income tax allowance for pensioners would always stay higher than the state pension.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Davey went paddleboarding on Lake Windermere in the marginal constituency of Westmorland and Lonsdale, highlighting the release of sewage in waterways.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] He pledged to abolish Ofwat and introduce a new water regulator to tackle the situation, in addition to proposing a ban on bonuses for chief executives of water companies.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Starmer was in West Sussex and emphasised his small town roots in his first big campaign speech.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 29 May, Labour's Wes Streeting promised a 18-week NHS waiting target within five years of a Labour government.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour also pledged to double the number of NHS scanners in England.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On the same day Starmer denied that Diane Abbott had been blocked as a candidate amid differing reports.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Abbott had been elected as a Labour MP, but had been suspended from the parliamentary party for a brief period.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] There was controversy about further Labour Party candidate selections, with several candidates on the left of the party being excluded.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Abbott said she had been barred from standing as a Labour Party candidate at the election, but Starmer later said she would be "free" to stand as a Labour candidate.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 30 May, both the Conservatives and Labour ruled out any rise in value-added tax.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Màiri McAllan claimed that only her party, the SNP, offered Scotland a route back into the European Union, making Pro-Europeanism part of the party's campaign.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Reform UK proposed an immigration tax on British firms who employ foreign workers.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Carla Denyer and Adrian Ramsay launched the Green Party of England and Wales campaign in Bristol.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Rhun ap Iorwerth launched the Plaid Cymru campaign in Bangor.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] George Galloway launched the Workers Party of Britain campaign in Ashton-under-Lyne.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 31 May, the Conservatives announced new "pride in places" pledges, including new rules to tackle anti-social behaviour, rolling out the hot-spot policing programme to more areas, and more town regeneration projects.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives also unveiled plans for fly-tippers to get points on their driving licences and other new measures to protect the environment.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 2 June, Labour pledged to reduce record high legal immigration to the United Kingdom by improving training for British workers.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Net migration to the UK was 685,000 in 2023.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour also focused on national security, with Starmer reaffirming his commitment to a "nuclear deterrent triple lock", including building four new nuclear submarines.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A YouGov poll conducted on the same day put Labour on course for the party's biggest election victory in history, beating Tony Blair's 1997 landslide.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 4 June, Farage launched his campaign in Clacton.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 6 June, the Green Party announced plans to invest an extra £50 billion a year for the NHS by raising taxes on the top 1% of earners.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives announced a policy on expanding child benefit for higher-earners.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour also announced communities will be given powers to transform derelict areas into parks and green spaces.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour's countryside protection plan would also include the planting new national forests, taskforces for tree-planting and flood resilience, new river pathways, and a commitment to revive nature.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Green spaces would be a requirement in the development of new housing and town plans.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Both Sunak and Starmer attended D-Day commemorations in Normandy on 6 June, the 80th anniversary of Operation Neptune.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Sunak angered veterans and was widely criticised for leaving early to do an interview with ITV.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Starmer met with Volodymyr Zelenskyy and King Charles III during the D-Day commemorations, and said that Sunak "has to answer for his actions".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Sunak apologised the next day and apologised again on 10 June.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Farage was among those critical of Sunak over his leaving the D-Day events, saying on 7 June that Sunak did not understand "our culture".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Conservative and Labour politicians criticised these words as being a racist attack on Sunak, which Farage denied.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 10 June, Labour pledged 100,000 new childcare places and more than 3,000 new nurseries as part of its childcare plan.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour released its plan for small business on 8 June, which included pledges to ⁠replace the current business rates system and to tackle the skill shortage by creating a new public body, Skills England.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They also pledged to ⁠revitalise Britain's high streets and a new trade strategy.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrat manifesto *For a Fair Deal* was released on 10 June.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats also offered a lifelong skills grant, giving adults £5,000 to spend on improving their skills.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The party wants electoral reform, and pledged to introduce proportional representation for electing MPs, and local councillors in England, and cap donations to political parties.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Sunak released the Conservative manifesto *Clear Plan.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Secure Future.* on 11 June, addressing the economy, taxes, welfare, expanding free childcare, education, healthcare, environment, energy, transport, community, and crime.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The manifesto includes a pledge to abolish Stamp Duty on homes worth up to £425,000 for first time buyers and expand the Help to Buy scheme.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives also pledged a recruitment of 8,000 new police officers and a rollout of facial recognition technology.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Much of what has been proposed is already incorporated in the 2023 and 2024 budget.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Carla Denyer and Adrian Ramsay released the Green Party's manifesto *Real Hope.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Real Change.* on 12 June, which pledged more taxes on the highest earners, generating £70 billion a year to help tackle climate change and the NHS.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They also pledged increased spending for public services, free personal care in England, renationalisation of railway, water and energy, a green society, a wealth tax, a carbon tax, and a windfall tax on the profit of banks.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The manifesto promises quicker access to NHS dentistry and GPs and reductions in the hospital waiting list.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They would also reach net zero by 2040 and introduce rent controls.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 12 June Conservative minister Grant Shapps said in a radio interview that voters should support the Conservatives so as to prevent Labour winning "a super-majority", meaning a large majority (the UK Parliament does not have any formal supermajority rules).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This was interpreted by journalists as a possible and surprising admission of defeat.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It paralleled social media advertising by the Conservatives that also focused on urging votes not to give Starmer a large majority.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 13 June, Starmer released the Labour Party manifesto *Change*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It focused on economic growth, planning system reforms, infrastructure, clean energy, healthcare, education, childcare, crime, and strengthening workers' rights.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It includes wealth creation and "pro-business and pro-worker" policies.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The manifesto also pledged to give votes to 16-year olds, reform the House of Lords, and to tax private schools, with money generated going into improving state education.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The party guaranteed giving all areas of England devolution powers, in areas such as integrated transport, planning, skills, and health.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 17 June, Farage and Tice released the Reform UK manifesto, which they called a "contract".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It also pledged to accelerate transport infrastructure in coastal regions, Wales, the North, and the Midlands.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The party also wants to freeze non-essential immigration and recruit 40,000 new police officers.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Reform UK are the only major party to oppose the current net zero target made by the government.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Instead, it pledged to support the environment with more tree planting, more recycling and less single-use plastics.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Farage predicted Labour would win the election, but said he was planning to campaign for the next election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour's Rachel Reeves claimed Labour's green plans would create over 650,000 jobs.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats offered more cost-of-living help for rural communities.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Davey highlighted his manifesto pledge to build 380,000 new homes a year, 150,000 of which would be social homes.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 18 June, Labour pledged hundreds of new banking hubs, to ''breathe life'' into high streets.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour also promised a large increase of renewable energy jobs, backed by new green apprenticeships.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 19 June, both the SNP and Sinn Féin released their manifestos.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Sinn Féin manifesto called for greater devolution to Northern Ireland and for the UK and Irish governments to set a date for a referendum on the unification of Northern Ireland with the Republic of Ireland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Galloway released the Workers Party manifesto, *Britain Deserves Better,* which promised to improve "poverty pay" and provide more social housing.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It pledged the renationalisation of utility companies, free school meals for all children without means testing, free adult education, and to hold a referendum on the continued existence of the monarchy and proportional representation for elections.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Davies, the Secretary of State for Wales, told a BBC interview the polls were "clearly pointing at a large Labour majority", but added that he believed there was "no great optimism" from voters.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A potentially large Labour majority was also acknowledged by Jeremy Hunt, the Chancellor of the Exchequer, and Mel Stride, the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Alison McGarry, the Labour chair of Islington North, resigned from the Labour Party after being spotted campaigning for Corbyn; she resigned rather than face expulsion for breaking the party's rules on campaigning for a rival candidate.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 20 June, the parties focused on housing.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour pledged action to protect renters with new legal protections for tenants.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It would immediately ban Section 21 "no-fault" evictions, as part of plans to reform the private rented sector in England.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour also pledged to reform planning laws and build 1.5 million homes to spread homeownership.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They would also ensure new housing is supported by new local infrastructure (public transport, healthcare, schools), and pledged to build more housing near railway stations and on the 'grey belt' (disused car parks or industrial estates).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives offered stronger legal protections for tenants, including banning Section 21 "no-fault" evictions.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They said they would build 1.6 million new homes (including social housing) with new local infrastructure, prioritising brownfield development, while protecting the countryside.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats offered more protections for tenants, additional social housing, and more garden cities.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Also on 20 June, the Alliance Party in Northern Ireland launched their manifesto.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Its core policies include reforming the political institutions, dedicated funding for integrated education, a Green New Deal to decarbonise Northern Ireland's economy, childcare reforms, and lowering the voting age to 16.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 21 June, in an interview, Farage repeated comments he had made previously stating that the West and NATO provoked Russia's invasion of Ukraine.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] He was criticised for this by Sunak and Starmer.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] He also stated that Reform UK would lower the tax burden to encourage people into work.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Farage stated in another interview that he would remove university tuition fees if he won power for those studying science, technology, engineering, medicine or maths.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Reform UK have already pledged to scrap interest on student loans and to extend the loan capital repayment periods to 45 years.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Farage also declared his ambition for Reform UK to replace the Conservatives as the biggest right-wing party in Parliament.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives pledged a review of licensing laws and planning rules aimed at boosting pubs, restaurants and music venues.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour framed its 10-year science and R&D budget plans as part of its industrial strategy, with an aim of boosting workforce and regional development.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour and the Liberal Democrats also focused on water pollution and improving England's water quality.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour pledged to put failing water companies who do not meet ''high environmental standards'' under special measures, give regulators new powers to block the payment of bonuses to executives who pollute waterways, and criminal charges against persistent law breakers.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They also ensured independent monitoring of every outlet.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 24 June, Labour focused on NHS dentistry and health, pledged to hold a knife crime summit every year and halve incidents within a decade.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Greens pledged to end 'dental deserts' with £3 billion for new NHS contracts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats launched a mini-manifesto for carers.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It pledged to establish an independent living taskforce to help people live independently in their own homes, a new care worker's minimum wage to raise their pay by £2 an hour, and a new National Care Agency.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Sunak released the Scottish Conservatives' manifesto.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Starmer discussed a proposed Football Governance Bill, which will establish the new Independent Football Regulator.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives and Liberal Democrats have also committed to introducing an Independent Football Regulator.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats pledged to establish a series of "creative enterprise zones" across the UK to regenerate cultural output.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 26 June, Alex Salmond released the Alba Party manifesto.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Starmer pledged GP reforms, including the training of thousands more GPs, updating the NHS App, and bringing back the 'family doctor'.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour would also trial new "neighbourhood health centres".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Social Democratic and Labour Party also launched their manifesto on 26 June in Northern Ireland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It pledged a 'Marshall Plan' to tackle health, institutional reform, stronger environmental protection with an independent Environmental Protection Agency, and improving NI's financial settlement.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 27 June, Labour pledged to reform careers advice and work experience in schools for one million pupils, committing to deliver two weeks' worth of quality work experience for every young person, and recruit more than thousands of new careers advisers.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This is part of the party's wider plan to establish a "youth guarantee" of access to training, an apprenticeship or support to find work for all 18 to 21-year-olds.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 27 June, an undercover Channel 4 journalist secretly recorded members of Farage's campaign team using offensive racial, Islamophobic and homophobic language, also suggesting refugees should be used as "target practice".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In a statement, Farage said that he was "dismayed" at the "reprehensible" language.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Tice said that racist comments were "inappropriate".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Farage later accused Channel 4 of a "set-up", stating that one of the canvassers, Andrew Parker, had been an actor.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Farage stated that Parker had been "acting from the moment he came into the office", and cited video of Parker performing "rough-speaking" from his acting website.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Channel 4 denied that Parker was known to them prior to the report.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 29 June, the Liberal Democrats called for an 'emergency NHS budget' to hire more GPs.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Starmer hosted a major campaign rally, and stated in *The Guardian* "if you vote Labour on Thursday, the work of change begins.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] We will launch a new national mission to create wealth in every community.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] We'll get to work on repairing our public services with an immediate cash injection, alongside urgent reforms.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] And we will break with recent years by always putting country before party".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Greens announced a 'Charter for Small Business', which pledged £2 billion per year in grant funding for local authorities, regional mutual banks for investment in decarbonisation and local economic sustainability, and increasing annual public subsidies for rail and bus travel to £10 billion.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They also pledged free bus travel for under-18s.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Northern Ireland Conservatives also launched their manifesto.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 30 June, the Liberal Democrats pledged to double funding for Bereavement Support Payments, and to spend £440 million a year on support for bereaved families.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 2 July, the Greens announced its £8 billion education package would include scrapping tuition fees, providing free school meals for all children, a qualified counsellor in every school and college, and new special needs provision.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They also want to end formal testing in primary and secondary schools with a system of continuous assessment.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Former prime minister Boris Johnson campaigned for the Conservatives.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 3 July, the political parties made their closing arguments on the last day of campaigning, with Sunak stating he would "take full responsibility" for the result.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] At the end of the campaign, Labour maintained their significant lead in polling over the Conservatives, and had endorsements from celebrities, including Elton John.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 4 July, less than an hour before polls closed, Sunak's government announced the 2024 Dissolution Honours, with life peerages being given to 19 people, including former prime minister Theresa May and Cass Review author Hilary Cass.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 12 June 2024, it was reported that Conservative candidate and Parliamentary Private Secretary to the Prime Minister, Craig Williams had placed a £100 bet on the date of the election being in July, three days before the date was announced.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The bet was referred to the Gambling Commission to determine whether Williams had placed the bet based on confidential information, which could constitute a criminal offence.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Williams apologised for the bet, but neither he nor Sunak would answer whether he had inside information.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 19 June, a police protection officer assigned to Sunak was arrested for betting on the election date.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On the same day, it was also announced that Laura Saunders, the Conservative candidate for Bristol North West, was being investigated for betting on the election date.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Her husband, Tony Lee, was also being investigated by the Gambling Commission and took a leave of absence from his role as the party's director of campaigning on 19 June.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 25 June, both Williams and Saunders had their support for their candidacies withdrawn by the Conservative Party.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In April 2025, Williams and 14 others were charged with offences under the Gambling Act 2005.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Rishi Sunak challenged Keir Starmer to six televised debates.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Ed Davey declared his wish to be included in "any televised debates", although he would ultimately only be featured in one debate.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] On 29 May, it was announced that the first leaders' debate would be hosted by ITV News with Julie Etchingham as moderator, on 4 June.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Key topics were the cost of living crisis, the National Health Service (NHS), young people, education, immigration and tax policy.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Sunak said that Labour would cost households £2000 more in tax, which Starmer denied.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Sunak said this figure was calculated by "independent Treasury officials".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Fact checkers disputed the sum, stating it was based on assumptions made by political appointees and that the figure was over a four-year period.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Office for Statistics Regulation also criticised the claim on the grounds that it was presented without the listener knowing it was a sum over 4 years.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] A YouGov snap poll after the debate indicated that 46% of debate viewers thought Sunak had performed better, and 45% believed Starmer had performed better.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] A Savanta poll published the next day favoured Starmer 44% to Sunak 39%.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The debate was watched by 5.37 million viewers, making it the most-viewed programme of the week.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] An STV debate hosted by Colin Mackay took place on 3 June, which included Douglas Ross, Anas Sarwar, John Swinney and Alex Cole-Hamilton.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Another debate between these leaders (also including Lorna Slater) took place on 11 June, on BBC Scotland, hosted by Stephen Jardine.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] A BBC debate hosted by Mishal Husain took place on 7 June, which included Nigel Farage, Carla Denyer, Rhun ap Iorwerth, Daisy Cooper, Stephen Flynn, Angela Rayner and Penny Mordaunt.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] After the seven-way debate, a snap poll found that viewers considered Farage had won, followed by Rayner, but that Flynn, Denyer and Cooper scored best on doing a good job.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Another debate between these leaders took place on 13 June, with Julie Etchingham as moderator.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] On 12 June Sky News hosted a leaders' event in Grimsby hosted by Beth Rigby, including Starmer and Sunak, where they took questions from both Rigby and the audience.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The debate covered various topics, including the NHS, the economy, education, immigration, housing and their future plans in government.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Starmer started the event by saying he was putting the country ahead of his party, bringing Labour "back into the service of working people".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] He went on to attack the Conservatives on tax policy, saying that "the Tories are in no position to lecture anyone about tax rises".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] 64% of those questioned by YouGov immediately following the debate said that Starmer had performed better, compared to 36% who said Sunak had performed better.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Channel 4 News hosted a debate on 18 June with all seven of the main parties focusing solely on the issues of immigration and law and order.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Other BBC debates included three *Question Time* specials, two hosted by Fiona Bruce on 20 and 28 June, and one hosted by Bethan Rhys Roberts on 24 June.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] There was a BBC Cymru Wales debate on 21 June; and a debate between Sunak and Starmer hosted by Husain took place on 26 June.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] There was also a BBC debate on 27 June involving the five largest Northern Irish political parties.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In addition to the debates, the BBC and ITV broadcast programmes in which the leaders of the main parties were interviewed at length.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Nick Robinson did BBC *Panorama* interviews with all the leaders of the main parties.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Sunak's *Tonight* interview with Paul Brand drew substantial coverage in the week prior to broadcast, as Sunak controversially departed the D-Day commemorations early to attend.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] It was later revealed that the interview slot had been chosen by Sunak and his team from a range of options offered by ITN.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Newspapers, organisations, and individuals endorsed parties or individual candidates for the election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] There were 4,515 candidates standing, which constitutes a record number, with a mean of 6.95 candidates per constituency.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] No seat had fewer than five people contesting it; Rishi Sunak's Richmond and Northallerton seat had the most candidates, with thirteen.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In March 2022, Labour abandoned all-women shortlists, citing legal advice that continuing to use them for choosing parliamentary candidates would be an unlawful practice under the Equality Act 2010, since the majority of Labour MPs were now women.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In March 2024, Reform UK announced an electoral pact with the Northern Irish unionist party TUV.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The TUV applied to run candidates as "TUV/Reform UK" on ballot papers, but this was rejected by the Electoral Office.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Nigel Farage unilaterally ended this deal by endorsing two competing candidates from the Democratic Unionist Party on 10 June.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Reform UK also announced a pact with the Social Democratic Party (SDP), a minor socially conservative and economically left-wing party, in some seats.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Discussion around the campaign was focused on the prospect of a change in government, as Labour maintained significant leads in opinion polling over the Conservatives, with one in five voters voting tactically.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Projections four weeks before the vote indicated a landslide victory for Labour that surpassed the one achieved by Tony Blair at the 1997 general election, while comparisons were made in the media to the 1993 Canadian federal election due to the prospect of a potential Conservative wipeout.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] A YouGov poll conducted four weeks before the vote suggested that Labour was on course for the party's biggest election victory in history, beating Blair's 1997 landslide.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The poll indicated Labour could win 422 seats, while the Conservatives were projected to win 140 seats.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Halfway through the campaign, psephologist John Curtice summarised the polls as having shown little change in the first two weeks of the campaign but that they had then shown some clear shifts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Conservatives led the polls for the two years following the 2019 general election, which included Brexit, the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic and vaccine rollout during the leadership of Boris Johnson.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Labour took a lead following the Partygate scandal and maintained this through the Liz Truss and Rishi Sunak premierships until the 2024 election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Opinion polls conducted for the 2024 United Kingdom general election from the 2019 general election with a local regressions (LOESS) trend line for each party.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Opinion polls conducted during the 2024 general election campaign period from 22 May to 4 July with a local regression (LOESS) trend line for each party.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] An exit poll conducted by Ipsos for the BBC, ITV, and Sky News was published at the end of voting at 22:00, predicting the number of seats for each party.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] At about 4 am on 5 July, the BBC released a new projection, combining the exit poll with the results coming in.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Voting closed at 22:00, which was followed by an exit poll.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The first seat, Houghton and Sunderland South, was declared at 23:15 with Bridget Phillipson winning for Labour.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Inverness, Skye and West Ross-shire was the last seat to declare, due to multiple recounts after the election, with Angus MacDonald winning for the Liberal Democrats on the afternoon of 6 July.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Notably, the 2024 election was the most unrepresentative in UK history, with Labour receiving the lowest percentage of the popular vote for a governing party in any general election since record-keeping of the popular vote began in 1830.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The result was a landslide win for Labour and a historic loss for the Conservatives.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Conservatives won no seats in Wales or various English counties, including Cornwall and Oxfordshire (the latter historically known for having several safe Conservative seats), and they only won one seat in North East England.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Keir Starmer became the fourth prime minister in a two-year period.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Turnout, at 59.9%, was the second lowest since records began in 1885 with only 2001 being lower at 59.4%.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Liberal Democrats made significant gains to reach their highest ever number of seats, mostly gaining Conservative seats in Southern England.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Co-operative Party, which is in an electoral pact with the Labour Party, and whose MPs are designated as Labour Co-op, also had its best ever result.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] It elected 43 MPs, surpassing its previous record of 38 seats in the 2017 election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] These MPs are typically included in the overall Labour total.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Reform UK had MPs elected to the Commons for the first time.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Their leader, Nigel Farage, was elected to Parliament on what was his eighth attempt.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Green Party of England and Wales also won a record number of seats.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The party's two co-leaders, Carla Denyer and Adrian Ramsay, both entered Parliament for the first time.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Scottish National Party (SNP) lost around three quarters of its seats to Scottish Labour.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Labour returned to being the largest party in Scotland and remained so in Wales, although their vote share fell in Wales.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Because the Democratic Unionist Party lost 3 seats, Sinn Féin won the most seats in Northern Ireland, making it the first time an Irish nationalist party was the largest party in Parliament from Northern Ireland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Traditional Unionist Voice entered the Commons for the first time.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In North Down, independent Unionist candidate Alex Easton emerged victorious over the Alliance Party incumbent Stephen Farry, resulting in the election of a total of six independent MPs across the UK.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Additionally, Wes Streeting retained his Ilford North constituency by a margin of only 528 votes following a challenge by independent British-Palestinian candidate Leanne Mohamad, while prominent Labour MP Jess Phillips retained her Birmingham Yardley constituency by a margin of 693 votes.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Labour candidate Paul Waugh won the seat of Rochdale from incumbent MP George Galloway, despite the constituency's sizeable Muslim population.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In Islington North, Jeremy Corbyn defeated the Labour candidate with a majority of 7,247; Corbyn is a prominent activist for Palestinian solidarity.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In September 2024, Corbyn went on to form the Independent Alliance group in parliament with four of the other five elected independent MPs.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The combined vote share for Labour and the Conservatives reached a record low, with smaller parties doing well.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Liberal Democrats recorded their best ever seat result (72), despite receiving only around half the votes they did in 2010, and fewer votes overall than Reform, although the party's seat share was again lower than its share of the vote.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] As Starmer's government was elected with the lowest share of the vote of any majority party on record, journalist Fraser Nelson described Labour's electoral success as a "Potemkin landslide".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] An editorial from *The Guardian* described the result as a "crisis of electoral legitimacy" for the incoming Labour government.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Gallagher index gave the election a 23.67 score, making it the least proportionate election in modern UK history according to the index, as well as the 5th least proportional result worldwide as of 2024.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] According to political scientist John Curtice, the 2024 election was the most disproportional in British history and Labour's parliamentary majority was "heavily exaggerated" by the voting system.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Advocacy group Make Votes Matter found that 58% of voters did not vote for their elected MP.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Make Votes Matter spokesman Steve Gilmore, Electoral Reform Society chief Darren Hughes, Reform UK leader Nigel Farage and the Green Party of England and Wales co-leader Adrian Ramsay were among the figures that called for electoral reform in the wake of the election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The campaigners said it was the "most disproportionate election in [British] history".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The election resulted in more widespread marginality, with 31% of seats won on margins up to 10% compared with 22% in the 2019 election.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The average seat majority fell from 26% in 2019 to 16% in 2024.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Below is listed YouGov's demographic breakdown.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Below is listed Ipsos's demographic breakdown.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] At around 04:45 on 5 July, Sunak conceded defeat to Starmer at the declaration at Sunak's seat of Richmond and Northallerton, before Labour had officially secured a majority.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/2024-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Starmer succeeded Sunak as prime minister, ending 14 years of the Conservatives in government.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] The **24-hour news cycle** (or **24/7 news cycle**) is the 24-hour investigation and reporting of news or informational content, typically by for-profit media agencies engaged in mass communications.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] The proliferation of mass media and the growth of the cable television market in recent decades has increased competition for audience and advertiser attention, prompting agencies to seek to deliver the latest news in the most compelling manner possible in order to remain ahead of competitors.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] Television, radio, print, online and mobile app news media all have many suppliers that want to be relevant to their audiences, principally by delivering the news first.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] Although all-news radio stations had operated for decades prior, the 24-hour news cycle truly arrived with the advent of cable television channels dedicated exclusively to news in the 1980s.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] This shift brought about a much faster pace of news production, and an increased demand for continuous reporting with real-time updates.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] This stood in marked contrast to the slower pacing of the news cycle seen previously in printed dailies.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] The high premium on immediate coverage would further increase with the advent of online news.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] A complete news cycle consists of the media reporting on an event, followed by it reporting on public and organizational reactions to previous reports.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] The advent of 24-hour cable and satellite television news channels and, in more recent times, of news sources on the World Wide Web (including blogs), has considerably shortened the timeframe within which this process occurs.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] These advancements created the earliest shifts in norms surrounding communication, information, and the speed at which the latter was expected and able to be made available to the general viewing public.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] In the years that followed, the urgency with which news was received and sought after increased proportionately to improvements in the speed and quality of communications systems.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] Ted Turner and Reese Schonfeld pioneered the concept of 24-hour network news with their founding of Cable News Network (CNN) in 1979.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] In 2015, *Time* magazine noted that the 1995 O.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] Simpson murder case was a significant early example of the 24-hour news cycle.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] According to former journalists Bill Kovach and Tom Rosenstiel, 24-hour news creates wild competition among media organizations for audience share.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] This, coupled with the profit demand of their corporate ownership, has led to a decline in journalistic standards.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] In their book *Warp Speed: America in the Age of Mixed Media*, they write that "the press has moved toward sensationalism, entertainment, and opinion" and away from traditional values of verification, proportion, relevance, depth, and quality of interpretation.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] They fear these values will be replaced by a "journalism of assertion" which de-emphasizes whether a claim is valid and encourages putting a claim into the arena of public discussion as quickly as possible.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] He ultimately felt it best remedied, though, by increased competition through expansion of the marketplace.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] The effect of constant and overbearing exposure to information on regional or global events on individual and group psychology is pronounced.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] A Civil War era account by Oliver Wendell Holmes Sr., detailing the "war fever" afflicting men of the time, serves as one of the earliest observations on the psychological effects of relatively instantaneous communication.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hour-news-cycle] Holmes spoke of a "nervous restlessness" within which "men [could] not think, or [sic.] write, or attend to their ordinary business".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hours-tv-programme] The programme brought together the production teams from two BBC television programmes: *Gallery*, a weekly political programme, and *Tonight*, an early-evening magazine programme.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hours-tv-programme] The original editors were Tony Whitby from *Tonight* and Derrick Amoore from *Gallery*, and it later came to be led by Anthony Smith.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hours-tv-programme] Presenter Cliff Michelmore was the first lead anchor for *24 Hours*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hours-tv-programme] With him in the studio were Kenneth Allsop, Michael Barratt and Robert McKenzie, a professor of politics at the London School of Economics (LSE).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hours-tv-programme] Towards the end of its run David Dimbleby became the main presenter.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hours-tv-programme] Production paperwork, *Radio Times* and BBC Archive library all list the title "Twenty-Four Hours" in words, but the programme's logo used numerals: "24 Hours".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hours-tv-programme] The programme originally had a fluid start time somewhere after 10 pm.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hours-tv-programme] The decision to give it a fixed start time of 9:55 pm was taken in 1967 following the establishment of ITN's peak-time *News at Ten* programme.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hours-tv-programme] Huw Wheldon, the then BBC Controller of Programmes, said that *24 Hours* "has become such a valuable part of our coverage of national and international affairs, that we feel we must give it a regular and predictable placing.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hours-tv-programme] David Attenborough ... who wants to put his BBC2 programmes on in such a way as to provide real choice for viewers, is driven mad by *Twenty-Four Hours* which has had to keep jumping about all over the place.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hours-tv-programme] Now we've got *Twenty-Four Hours* fixed at five-to-ten, we can handle all that!".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/24-hours-tv-programme] The run of *24 Hours* ended on 14 July 1972.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/3-mills-studios] In August 2004, the London Development Agency (LDA) acquired 3 Mills Studios.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/3-mills-studios] As parent organisation of the *Creative London* agency, the LDA's role included supporting business and skills, researching industry needs, and promoting London for film-making.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/3-mills-studios] The site is now one of London's most important film and television studios.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/3-mills-studios] Ownership transferred to the London Legacy Development Corporation in 2010 which is the organisation responsible for planning, developing, and managing the Olympic Park after the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios has over 75,000 sq ft (7,000 m2) of filming space, including 11 filming stages and nine rehearsal rooms.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/3-mills-studios] Stage 5 at 10,437 sq ft (969.6 m2) has a similar floor size to the Royal Albert Hall.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/3-mills-studios] There are nine rehearsal rooms on site: Rehearsal Room 6 at 2,507 sq ft (232.9 m2) is the largest and Rehearsal Room 3 at 280.9 sq ft (26.10 m2) is the smallest.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios has a large range of ancillary spaces including; production offices, props workshops, five prop stores ranging from 712 to 1,319 sq ft (66.1 to 122.5 m2), make-up rooms, and dressing rooms.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/3-mills-studios] Many feature films have been made at 3 Mills Studios, including *Legend*, *Topsy-Turvy*, *Sexy Beast*, *Eastern Promises*, *Attack the Block*, *Berberian Sound Studio*, *Ill Manors*, *Powder Room*, *Made in Dagenham*, *Never Let Me Go*, *Farming* and *Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios' main focus has been on television shows.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios has been home to BBC's *MasterChef* since 2014.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills was home to Channel 4's *Big Brother* for the first and second series along with the first series of *Celebrity Big Brother*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/3-mills-studios] Other clients include Matthew Bourne's New Adventures, English National Opera, Raymond Gubbay Limited, Shakespeare's Globe and English National Ballet, as well as advertisers for Versace, Audi, Waitrose, Nissan, Gillette, Samsung, Gucci, Topshop, B&Q and Adidas.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios also housed many rehearsals for the opening and closing ceremonies of the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The **BBC News** channel is a British free-to-air public broadcast television news channel owned and operated by the BBC.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The channel is based at and broadcasts from Broadcasting House in the West End of London from which it is anchored during British daytime, with overnight broadcasts anchored from Washington, D.C. and Singapore.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] It was launched as **BBC News 24** on 9 November 1997 at 17:30, as part of the BBC's foray into digital domestic television channels, becoming the first competitor to Sky News, which had been running since 1989.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] On 22 February 2006, the channel was named *News Channel of the Year* at the Royal Television Society Television Journalism Awards for the first time in its history.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The judges remarked that this was the year that the channel had "really come into its own." The channel won the accolade for a second time in 2017.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] From May 2007, viewers in the UK could watch the channel via the BBC News website.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In April 2008, the channel was renamed *BBC News* as part of a £550,000 rebranding of the BBC's news output, complete with a new studio and presentation.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The channel's international counterpart, formerly known as BBC World News, initially operated as a counterpart carrying international news, as well as selected programmes from the domestic service.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Unlike BBC News in the UK, which is a free-to-air channel funded by the licence fee, the world feed is a pay television service distributed by BBC Studios and funded by advertising.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Some of its programmes had been simulcast by the domestic BBC News channel, especially in the overnight hours.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Rolling news began in the UK on 5 February 1989 when Sky News was launched and on 16 January 1995, the BBC launched an international news channel BBC World.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] However it was meant for global audiences and was not normally available to viewers in the UK.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In May 1996, the BBC announced that it was to launch a UK rolling news service as part of its move into digital broadcasting.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] BBC News 24 went on air on 9 November 1997, nearly a year before digital television was launched in the UK and due to a lack of space on satellite, the channel was only available on cable, with an overnight shop window on BBC One when that channel was not on air.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] However, Sky News had complained about the costs associated with running a channel that only a minority of the UK's licence fee could view.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Sky News claimed that a number of British cable operators had been incentivised to carry News 24 (which, as a licence-fee funded channel was made available to such operators for free) in preference to the commercial Sky News.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] However, in September 1999 the European Commission ruled against a complaint made by Sky News that the publicly funded channel was unfair and illegal under EU law.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The Commission ruled that the licence fee should be considered state aid but that such aid was justified due to the public service remit of the BBC and that it did not exceed actual costs.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The advent of digital television in the United Kingdom in autumn 1998 saw the channel launch on Sky's new digital satellite service and a month later it started to broadcast via digital terrestrial television.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The 2004 report also claimed that the channel outperformed Sky News in both weekly and monthly reach in multichannel homes for the January 2004 period, and for the first time in two years moved ahead of Sky News in being perceived as the channel best for news.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In 2005, the Head of television news Peter Horrocks outlined plans to provide more funding and resources for the channel and shift the corporation's emphasis regarding news away from the traditional BBC One bulletins and across to the rolling news channel.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The introduction of simulcasts of the main bulletins on the channel was to allow the news bulletins to pool resources rather than work against each other at key times in the face of competition, particularly from Sky News.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] On 21 April 2008, BBC News 24 was renamed "BBC News" on the channel itself, and referred to as the "BBC News Channel" on other BBC services.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] This was part of the Creative Futures plan, launched in 2006, to bring all BBC News output under the single brand name.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The BBC News Channel moved from the Studio N8 set, which became home to BBC World News, to what was the home of the national news in Studio N6, allowing the channel to share its set with the *BBC News at One* and the *BBC News at Ten* – with other bulletins moving to Studio TC7.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The channel relocated, along with the remaining BBC News services at Television Centre, to the newly refurbished Broadcasting House on 18 March 2013 at 13:00 GMT.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Presentation and on-screen graphics were refreshed, with new full HD studios and a live newsroom backdrop.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Moving cameras in the newsroom form part of the top of the hour title sequence and are used at the start of weather bulletins.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] On 26 May 2022, as part of planned cuts and streamlining across the broadcaster, the BBC announced plans for consolidation of the domestic BBC News channel in the UK with BBC World News.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The domestic and international versions would share content, while maintaining the ability to opt out from the shared feed for domestic coverage if warranted.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The BBC promoted that the service would offer "new flagship programmes built around high-profile journalists, and programmes commissioned for multiple platforms".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The BBC announced a new presenter line-up for the merged service in February 2023, led by Matthew Amroliwala, Christian Fraser, Yalda Hakim, Lucy Hockings, and Maryam Moshiri.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Overall, the changes resulted in the layoffs of about 50 employees, including presenters David Eades, Joanna Gosling, and Tim Willcox.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Yalda Hakim left the channel to join Sky News in September 2023, meaning that Maryam Moshiri could have her own programme in the slot of Hakim's former Daily Global programme.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In February 2024, Ben Brown, Geeta Guru-Murthy, and Anita McVeigh rejoined the news channel after a year off air as chief presenters.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] During the 2024 general election campaign, BBC News temporarily unwound the unified service, and reverted to broadcasting a domestic feed of rolling coverage from 9 a.m. to 8 p.m. daily, as well as an additional UK-specific bulletin at 11 p.m. following *Newsnight*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] This continued through the State Opening of Parliament, after which the prior schedule was reinstated beginning 18 July.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The 11 p.m. bulletin remained until October 2024, when it was replaced with *World News America*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In January 2025, the UK feed dropped its simulcast of *BBC Breakfast* as a pilot, with world feed programming now carried in its timeslot; executive news editor Paul Royall considered the simulcast redundant, citing that the majority of its viewership came from BBC One and iPlayer.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The pilot ended in the spring but was reinstated again on 29 October 2025, seemingly now on a permanent basis.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] On 16 July 2013, the BBC announced that a high-definition (HD) simulcast of BBC News would be launched by early 2014.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] HD output from BBC News has been simulcast on BBC One HD and BBC Two HD since the move to Broadcasting House in March 2013.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The channel launched on 10 December 2013 (at an earlier date than originally planned) and rolled out nationwide over the next six months (as did BBC Four HD, CBBC HD and CBeebies HD).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] BBC News HD was removed from Freeview on 30 June 2022 due to the closure of the COM7 multiplex.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] There are HD versions of BBC News on BBC iPlayer, Freesat channel 200, Sky channel 503, and Virgin Media channel 601.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The BBC maintains guidelines for procedures to be taken for breaking news.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] With domestic news, the correspondent first recorded a "generic minute" summary (for use by all stations and channels) and then priority was to report on BBC Radio 5 Live, then on the BBC News channel and any other programmes that are on air.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Since 5 Live's move to Manchester, this has been reversed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] For foreign news, first a "generic minute" is recorded, then reports are to World Service radio, then the reporter talks to any other programmes that are on air.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] A key claim made by Lord Lambert in his report had been that the channel was slower to react to breaking news compared with its main rival Sky News.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] To counteract this, a new feature introduced with the 2003 relaunch was a "breaking news sting": a globe shown briefly onscreen to direct a viewer's attention to the breaking news.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The graphics relaunch in January 2007 saw the globe sting replaced by a red strapline to highlight the breaking story immediately.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] To complement this, a permanent live news ticker had earlier been introduced in 2006: this had previously been in use only sporadically.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] News statements are shown as continuously scrolling upper-case text located at the bottom of the screen; some past ambiguities noted have included spelling the plural of MPs as "MPS", together with other occasional spelling and grammatical errors.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The design of this ticker was slightly altered with the 2007 graphics redesign and from June turned red to indicate breaking news, as *Newswatch* reported viewers' confusion.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The ticker was removed during trails and weather forecasts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] A new set of graphics, including a change to font style, was officially launched in July 2019 although it was broadcast in error up to a couple of months before.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The news ticker, which had been a long-running feature of the Channel, was replaced by a flipper as stories no longer scroll across the screen.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The headlines now have a limited length and appear in full in turn.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The word "BREAKING" may appear on screen and flash to indicate breaking news.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Occasionally a breaking news sting may appear on the Channel to call attention to breaking news.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] This sting gained some notoriety in June 2017 when a technical error caused it to appear several times in a row, delaying the start of the *BBC News at Ten*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Usually the BBC News Channel crosses over to live events, such as press conferences, without using the sting and the presenter on air introduces what viewers are seeing.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The BBC began simulcasting the channel overnight on terrestrial channel BBC One with the launch of the channel, ending the tradition of a closedown but at the same time effectively making the service available to many more viewers.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In the early 2000s, BBC Two also started simulcasting the channel, although the weekend morning show *Weekend 24* had been simulcast on the channel in the early days.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In 2020, shared programming between BBC One and the News Channel often included the UK Government's Coronavirus Daily Update.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] This was usually broadcast during late afternoons when the Government made announcements.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Coverage of major events has also been simulcast on BBC World News.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Currently, overnight viewers receive 25-minute editions of BBC News every hour, and on weekdays 23:00–02:00 receive *Newsday*, live from Singapore and from London which also includes *Business Today* and *Sportsday* between 00:30 and 01:00 and also between 01:30 and 02:00.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] *The Briefing* airs between 05:00 and 06:00 on weekdays.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] These simulcasts were expanded as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The BBC introduced a streamlined schedule and the News Channel and BBC World News now share major parts of evening and weekend coverage.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] From August 2020 this was changed and made permanent to 10:00 to 12:00 and on weekdays 19:00 to 06:00, with opt-outs for *BBC News at Ten* and half an hour at 20:30, weekends 21:00 to 06:00, apart from the evening BBC One bulletin.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] World News is no longer simulcasted, given that the channel has been merged with the domestic provision, thereby any programming on the News Channel is broadcast as the channel says "Around the world and across the UK".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] BBC Two simulcasts the News Channel on weekday mornings from 09:00 until 12:15 or 13:00.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Coverage switches to BBC One in the form of the simulcast *BBC News at One*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The *BBC News at One* may be broadcast on BBC One only however during periods of breaking news or major announcements in the House of Commons carried only on the News Channel, if it's an international story coverage will switch for the hour to simulcast with BBC World News.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] A similar arrangement applies for the *BBC News at Six*, generally simulcast on both BBC One and the News Channel but, as ever, subject to change for breaking news for the News Channel.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The *BBC News at Ten* began simulcasting on the channel on 30 January 2006 as part of the *Ten O'Clock Newshour*, followed by extended sport and business news updates.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] During the summer, the hour-long programme *News 24 Sunday* was broadcast both on BBC One and the BBC News Channel at 09:00, to replace *The Andrew Marr Show*, which is off air.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] It was presented by a news presenter, and came from the main News channel studio.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The programme was made up mostly of interviews focusing on current affairs, and included a full paper review, a weather summary, and a news update at 09:00, 09:30 and 10:00.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] *Sunday Morning Live* and alternative programming now fill this slot.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] From 2013, a new programme was created for BBC Two for 11:00–12:00 weekdays, consisting of 30 minutes of domestic news and 30 minutes of BBC World News.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] On Wednesdays, when parliament is sitting the latter is replaced by the *Daily Politics* for coverage of Prime Minister's Questions (PMQ).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In March 2016 the channel started showing *Newsnight* at 23:15.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The coverage from 10:00 to 13:00 on BBC Two and the News Channel is part of three-hour block of *BBC World News* simulcast due to the Coronavirus Pandemic.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] However, by the end of 2021 the simulcast had been cut back to a single hour on weekdays, between 10:00 and 11:00 with all-morning simulcasts continuing at the weekend.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] BBC World News produces the three-hour BBC News / BBC World News simulcast between 19:00 to 22:00 and 23:00 to 06:00, including one edition of *The Papers*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] From August 2020 this was changed and made permanent to 10:00 to 12:00 and on weekdays 19:00 to 06:00, with opt-outs for BBC News at Ten and half an hour at 20:30, weekends 21:00 to 06:00, these exclude BBC One bulletin.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] BBC News currently simulcasts all of BBC Television's main BBC One news bulletins – BBC News at One, BBC News at Six and BBC News at Ten.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] On Wednesdays BBC News simulcasts much of *Politics Live* which is broadcast on BBC Two to provide coverage of Prime Minister's Questions.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] After the News at 10, *Newsnight* is also aired on the BBC News Channel.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Weekend BBC One news bulletins are not shown on the BBC News Channel.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] All network simulcasts are broadcast on the domestic feed only.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Other programmes previous broadcast on BBC News Channel included *Head 2 Head*, *E24*, *The Record Europe*, *Politics Europe* and *News 24 Tonight*, a weekday evening programme which ran from 2005 to 2008, providing a round up of the day's news.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] As part of budget cuts, major changes to the channel were announced in late 2014 / early 2015.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] This included axing some bulletins and replacing them with *Victoria Derbyshire* and *BBC Business Live* with Sally Bundock and Ben Thompson in the morning.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The 00:00 edition was replaced on Sundays–Thursday with *Newsday* and on Friday-Saturday a standard edition of *BBC World News*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] On 1 October 2007, BBC World News started broadcasting *BBC World News America* and *World News Today* at 00:00 and 03:00 GMT respectively.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] *World News Today* was simulcast on the BBC News channel at 03:00 GMT.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] *BBC World News America* used to be aired as a reduced length, time-delayed version at 00:30 GMT, with *ABC World News Tonight with David Muir* also being shown at 01:30 every Tuesday-Friday.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The programme acts as a morning news bulletin for the Asia-Pacific region and is broadcast as a double-headed news bulletin with Rico Hizon in Singapore and Babita Sharma in London.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] *Asia Business Report* and *Sport Today* are aired at the back of the first three hours of *Newsday*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] But Newsday changed to 23:00–02:00 on BBC News a year later meaning Mike Embley presents Tuesday-Friday *BBC World News* 23:00–02:00 with Kasia Madera on Saturdays and Daniela Ritorto 00:00–06:00 Sunday, 02:00–05:00 Friday/Monday.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In June 2015, BBC News began simulcasting *Outside Source with Ros Atkins* on Mondays-Thursday at (during major stories 18:00) / at 21:00 and a new edition of *World News Today* Friday-Sunday at (during major stories Monday-Friday 19:00) 21:00.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Since January 2017, they began simulcasting *Beyond 100 Days* (previously '100 Days*and*100 Days +) Monday to Thursday at 19:00, presented from London and Washington.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] During August, *Beyond 100 Days* is replaced by another edition of *World News Today*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] On 26 May 2022, as part of planned cuts and streamlining to create a "digital first" broadcaster, the BBC announced plans to consolidate the BBC News and BBC World News networks into a single service under the "BBC News" name.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The merged service was slated to launch in April 2023, with the BBC stating that it would offer "new flagship programmes built around high-profile journalists, and programmes commissioned for multiple platforms".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The international version of the BBC News channel remains an advertising-supported service distributed by the corporation's commercial arm, BBC Studios.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The domestic channel may opt out from the shared schedule to provide coverage of UK-specific breaking news, and would continue to carry UK-specific programmes (such as simulcasts of BBC One bulletins and *Newsnight*) that are not cleared by the international channel.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] By the end of 2022, sharing had extended to 23:00–06:00 UK time, BBC News and BBC World News simulcast for the first 25 minutes of each hour with world news shown all through the simulcasts.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In addition, the 10:00 hour on weekdays was simulcast and at the weekend, simulcasts run throughout the morning UK-time.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The two channels also simulcast between 19:00 and 22:00.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] UK-specific rolling coverage had, by now, been restricted to daytime hours.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] As of Wednesday 15 January 2025, The UK feed has begun to simulcast the international feed from the hours of 05:00 to 13:00 BST until it breaks away for *BBC News at One*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] UK Viewers are now able to watch the 06:30 and 07:30 editions of *Business Today* which were formally shown on the international feed only.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The international feed broke away at 10:30 BST to show *HardTalk* until that programme ended in March 2025.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] At 17:30 BST *Focus on Africa* is shown whilst the UK feed stays with *Verified Live*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] On occasions where there is a significant global story or if there is a delay to the network bulletin, the channel simulcasts the 18:00 editions of *The World Today* and the 22:00 editions of *World News America*, instead of *BBC News at Ten* and *BBC News at Six*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] It is mentioned that in the case of major UK breaking news, *BBC Breakfast* would be carried on the BBC News Channel.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Since 5 March 2012, sports bulletins come from the *BBC Sport Centre* in MediaCityUK in Salford Quays, where the sports network BBC Radio 5 Live is also based.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Headlines are usually provided at 15 minutes past the hour with a full bulletin after the bottom-of-the-hour headlines.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] There are also extended sports bulletins per day, entitled *Sportsday* or *Sport Today* (when simulcasting with BBC World News) broadcast at 00:45, 01:45, 02:45, 03:45, 13:30, 18:30, 19:30 (weekends only), 22:30 (weekdays only).
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Each bulletin is read by a single sports presenter, with the exception of Saturday *Sportsday*, which is double headed.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The channel's sports bulletins (internally known as Sport 24) have always had a separate, dedicated production gallery, which is also responsible for the graphics.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Bulletins during *BBC Breakfast* are presented by Sally Nugent or Mike Bushell, with the latter also appearing on other sports bulletins on the channel.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] As of March 2019 the main sports presenters on the channel are Olly Foster, Gavin Ramjaun, Katie Gornall, Chetan Pathak, Katherine Downes, Tulsen Tollett, Lizzie Greenwood-Hughes and John Watson.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Until March 2012, bulletins came from the News Channel studio at the quarter to the hour.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Presenters for bulletins on the channel have included: Reshmin Chowdhury, Amanda Davies, Sean Fletcher, Matt Gooderick, Celina Hinchcliffe, Rachael Hodges, Damian Johnson, Adnan Nawaz and Olympic gold medallist turned journalist Matthew Pinsent.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Before BBC News moved to Broadcasting House, an hourly business update was included during the weekday schedule from the BBC Business Unit.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] There were two shifts, from 08:30 to 14:00 and 14:00 to 23:00, presented by Penny Haslam, Maryam Moshiri, Ben Thompson, Adam Parsons, Susannah Streeter, Joe Lynam, Sara Coburn or Sally Eden.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] News Channel updates were usually broadcast at 40 minutes past the hour between 08:00 and 23:00.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The 21:40 round-up was often earlier and the 22:40 bulletin is an extended round-up of the day's business news.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Until May 2009, the business updates on the BBC News Channel were broadcast from one of the London Stock Exchange's studios in central London.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] From then until March 2013 the bulletins were provided from the channel's studio at BBC Television Centre.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The business updates were axed in March 2013 as part of the BBC's Delivering Quality First plan.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] But after complaints returned in November 2013.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Stock market updates now only appear during the quarter-to-the-hour headlines.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Rachel Horne is the main presenter from 13:30 to 18:00, with Vishala Sri-Pathma, Alice Baxter, Jamie Robertson, Aaron Heslehurst and Sally Bundock.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] There is normally an extended bulletin at 16:45 when the main business stories of the day are discussed on *Afternoon Live*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Bundock and Thompson present *Business Live* on weekdays at 08:30.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Declan Curry presented *Your Money*, a weekly round-up on a Saturday morning.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Alice Baxter and Sally Bundock presented *World Business Report*.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The channel was criticised at launch for its style of presentation, with accusations of it being less authoritative than the BBC One news bulletins, with presenters appearing on-screen without jackets.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Jenny Abramsky had originally planned to have a television version of the informal news radio channel BBC Radio 5 Live, or a TV version of Radio 4 News FM both of which she had run.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The bright design of the set was also blamed for this – one insider reportedly described it as a "car crash in a shower" – and was subject to the network relaunch on 25 October 1999.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The channel swapped studios with sister channel BBC World, moving to studio N8 within the newsroom, where it remained until 2008.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] New music and title sequences accompanied this set change, following the look of newly relaunched BBC One bulletins.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Graphics and titles were developed by the Lambie-Nairn design agency and were gradually rolled out across the whole of BBC News, including a similar design for regional news starting with *Newsroom South East* and the three 'BBC Nations' – Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The similarity of main BBC News output was intended to increase the credibility of the channel as well as aiding cross-channel promotion.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] A graphics relaunch in January 2007 saw the channel updated, with redesigned headline straplines, a redesigned 'digital on-screen graphic' and repositioned clock.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The clock was originally placed to the left hand side of the channel name though following complaints that this could only be viewed in widescreen, it was moved to the right in February 2007.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Bulletins on BBC World News and BBC One also introduced similar graphics and title sequences on the same day.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In 2008, the graphics were again relaunched, using the style introduced in 2007 and a new colour scheme.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The typeface of the on-screen text was changed from Helvetica to Gill Sans.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In 2013 the graphics were changed again, to coincide with the move to New Broadcasting House.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The typeface was changed back to Helvetica.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] These were updated again in July 2019 when the BBC redesigned its on-air look with the growth of television viewing on smartphones and tablets.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] These included again redesigned, larger headline straplines sharply contrasting with the background (drawing criticism for obscuring content) using the BBC Reith typeface with larger text.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Despite this, the 2008 titles and music continue to be used for the updated local titles.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The Lambert Report into the channel's performance in 2002 called upon News 24 to develop a better brand of its own, to allow viewers to differentiate between itself and similar channels such as Sky News.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] As a direct result of this, a brand new style across all presentation for the channel launched on 8 December 2003 at 09:00.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Philip Hayton and Anna Jones were the first two presenters on the set, the relaunch of which had been put back a week due to previous power disruptions at Television Centre where the channel was based.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The new designs also featured a dynamic set of titles for the channel; the globe would begin spinning from where the main story was taking place, while the headline scrolled around in a ribbon; this was occasionally replaced by the BBC News logo.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The titles concluded with a red globe surrounded by a red stylised clamshell and BBC News ribbons forming above the BBC News logo.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Bulletins on BBC One moved into a new set in January 2003 although retained the previous ivory Lambie-Nairn titles until February 2004.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] News 24 updated the title colours slightly to match those of BBC One bulletins in time for the 50th anniversary of BBC television news on 5 July 2004.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] An important part of the channel's presentation since launch has been the top of the hour countdown sequence, since there is no presentation system with continuity announcers so the countdown provides a link to the beginning of the next hour.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] A similar musical device is used on BBC Radio 5 Live, and mirrors the pips on BBC Radio 4.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Previous styles have included a series of fictional flags set to music between 1997 and 1999 before the major relaunch, incorporating the new contemporary music composed by David Lowe, and graphics developed by Lambie-Nairn.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Various images, originally ivory numbers fully animated against a deep red background, were designed to fit the pace of the channel, and the music soon gained notoriety, and was often satirised and parodied in popular culture.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Images of life around the UK were added in replacement later with the same music, together with footage of the newsroom and exterior of Television Centre.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The 2003 relaunch saw a small change to this style with less of a metropolitan feel to the footage.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] A new sequence was introduced on 28 March 2005, designed and created by Red Bee Media and directed by Mark Chaudoir.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The full version ran for 60 seconds, though only around 30 seconds were usually shown on air.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The music was revised completely but the biggest change came in the footage used – reflecting the methods and nature of newsgathering, while a strong emphasis was placed on the BBC logo itself.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Satellite dishes are shown transmitting and receiving red "data streams".
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The sequence has since seen several remixes to the music and a change in visuals to focus more on the well-known journalists, with less footage of camera crews and production teams.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Changes have also seen the channel logo included during the sequences and at the end, as well as the fonts used for the time.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The conclusion of the countdown was altered in 2008 to feature the new presentation style, rather than a data stream moving in towards the camera.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Also in 2008, the graphic for the countdown changed, resembling the BBC One Rhythm and Movement idents, due to the logo being in a red square in the bottom left corner.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] To coincide with the move of BBC News to Broadcasting House, on 18 March 2013 the countdown was updated again along with several other presentation elements.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The countdown was also extended to 87 seconds, which was fully shown before the first hour from Broadcasting House.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In 2019, the countdown started using the BBC's new Reith font but otherwise retained the same style.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] A full three-minute version of the countdown music was made available on BBC News Online and David Lowe's own website after a remix on 16 May 2006.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] An international version of the countdown was launched on BBC World News on 5 September 2005 featuring more international content and similar music.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Various changes have been made to the music and visuals since then, with presentation following the style of BBC News.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The visuals in the sequence were updated on 10 May 2010.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In June 2011, further imagery was added relating to recent events, including the conflict in Libya and views of outside 10 Downing Street.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In January 2013, as part of the relocation of BBC News to Broadcasting House in Central London, BBC World News received a new countdown in the same style as the BBC News Channel's updated countdown, with some minor differences.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] In April 2021, a new "sombre" version of the countdown was played, with no "data streams" and slower shots of places within the UK, or in the case of the international version, timelapse shots across the world.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] Both were introduced to run up to programmes immediately following the death of Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, and were used again following the death of Queen Elizabeth II in 2022.
[src:bbc-news-british-tv-channel/bbc-news-british-tv-channel] The Daily Telegraph reported in November 2021, "BBC News reaches 370,000 for its best performing slots".
